      letter: 'D',
      shortDef: 'The portion of a homeowners policy that pays to repair or rebuild the physical structure of your home after a covered loss.',
      fullDef: 'Dwelling coverage (Coverage A in standard homeowners policies) pays to repair or rebuild the structure of your home—walls, roof, floors, built-in appliances, and attached structures like a garage—after a covered peril such as fire, windstorm, lightning, or vandalism. The coverage limit should equal the estimated cost to completely rebuild the home from scratch, not the market value or purchase price.\n\nInsuring to full replacement cost is critical. If your dwelling coverage limit is 20% below actual rebuild cost, the coinsurance clause in some policies will reduce every claim payment proportionally—even a partial loss. Rebuild costs have risen sharply due to material and labor inflation since 2020; homeowners should review coverage limits annually.\n\nDwelling coverage does not cover land value (land cannot burn down), contents (covered under personal property), or liability (a separate coverage). It also excludes flood and earthquake by default—those require separate policies.',
      example: 'When fire destroyed half the house, the $320,000 dwelling coverage limit covered the $285,000 reconstruction cost, leaving the homeowner with no out-of-pocket rebuild expenses.',
