      slug: 'leverage',
      letter: 'L',
      shortDef: 'Using borrowed money (a mortgage) to purchase an asset, amplifying both potential returns and potential losses.',
      fullDef: 'In real estate, leverage means using a mortgage to purchase a property, amplifying your returns on invested equity. If you buy a $300,000 property with $60,000 down, a 5% appreciation ($15,000) represents a 25% return on your $60,000 cash investment—leverage amplified a 5% gain into a 25% cash-on-cash return from appreciation alone.\n\nPositive leverage occurs when the return on the property (cap rate) exceeds the cost of debt (mortgage interest rate). Negative leverage—when borrowing costs exceed cap rate—destroys returns. Rising interest rates can flip a market from positive to negative leverage.\n\nLeverage also amplifies losses. A 10% decline in value at 80% LTV wipes out half the investor\'s equity. Investors should maintain adequate reserves, stress-test cash flows at higher vacancy and expense rates, and avoid over-leveraging.',
      example: 'By purchasing a $250,000 rental with a $50,000 down payment, the investor controlled $250,000 in assets with $50,000 of capital—a 5:1 leverage ratio that magnified returns from both cash flow and appreciation.',
      related: ['cap-rate', 'cash-on-cash-return', 'noi', 'debt-service-coverage-ratio'],
