      shortDef: 'NOI divided by annual mortgage payments; lenders use it to assess whether a property generates enough income to cover its debt.',
      fullDef: 'The debt service coverage ratio (DSCR) measures a property\'s ability to cover its mortgage payments from its own income. DSCR = NOI / Annual Debt Service. A DSCR of 1.0 means the property breaks even; 1.25 means the property generates 25% more income than needed to cover debt payments. Commercial and investment property lenders typically require a minimum DSCR of 1.20–1.25.\n\nDSCR is critical for loan underwriting because it captures the property\'s ability to service debt independently of the borrower\'s personal income. Some lenders offer "DSCR loans" where qualification is based entirely on the property\'s income—useful for self-employed investors or those with many properties.\n\nMonitoring DSCR helps identify properties under financial stress. A DSCR trending toward 1.0 signals rising vacancy, unexpected expenses, or inadequate rent growth—early warnings to take corrective action.',
      example: 'With $28,000 in annual NOI and $21,000 in annual mortgage payments, the eight-unit building had a DSCR of 1.33—above the lender\'s 1.25 minimum, qualifying for the commercial loan.',
