      shortDef: 'A quick valuation metric calculated by dividing property price by annual gross rents; lower GRM generally indicates better value.',
      fullDef: 'The gross rent multiplier (GRM) is a simple screening metric. GRM = Property Price / Annual Gross Rents. A property priced at $300,000 generating $36,000 in annual rent has a GRM of 8.3. A lower GRM indicates fewer dollars paid per dollar of rent—potentially better value.\n\nGRM is a blunt instrument because it ignores expenses, vacancy, and financing. Two properties with the same GRM but different expense structures can have very different cap rates. It is best used as a first-pass filter to quickly eliminate obviously overpriced properties before deeper analysis.\n\nTypical GRMs vary widely by market: high-demand coastal markets may see GRMs of 20–30+; Midwest value markets may be 5–10. Knowing the typical GRM range for your target market helps quickly identify properties that merit further analysis.',
      example: 'Comparing two duplexes—one at $280,000 with $30,000 in rents (GRM 9.3) and another at $320,000 with $30,000 (GRM 10.7)—the investor used GRM as a first screen to focus on the cheaper one.',
