      slug: 'due-diligence',
      letter: 'D',
      shortDef: 'The comprehensive investigation of a property\'s physical condition, financials, legal status, and market context before closing a purchase.',
      fullDef: 'Real estate due diligence is the systematic investigation a buyer conducts during the contract-to-close period. Physical due diligence includes property inspection, environmental assessment, roof inspection, HVAC evaluation, and structural review. Financial due diligence includes verifying actual rent rolls, reviewing leases, and analyzing trailing operating statements.\n\nLegal due diligence covers title search (confirming clear ownership and no encumbrances), survey review, zoning verification, and review of any existing easements or CC&Rs. For multi-family properties, tenant due diligence includes reviewing lease terms and payment histories.\n\nThe due diligence period (typically 10–30 days in residential, 30–60 days in commercial) is the buyer\'s window to investigate and negotiate price reductions—or walk away if issues are material. Rushing or skipping due diligence is one of the most expensive mistakes an investor can make.',
      example: 'During the 21-day due diligence period, the buyer\'s inspector discovered the building\'s boiler needed replacement; the buyer negotiated a $12,000 price reduction before closing.',
