      fullDef: 'Private money lending involves borrowing from individual investors or private lending companies rather than traditional banks. Private lenders evaluate primarily on the deal\'s collateral (the property) and the borrower\'s track record rather than extensive documentation. Loans are typically short-term (6–24 months), interest-only, at rates of 8–14%, with origination points of 1–4%.\n\nPrivate money fills gaps that conventional financing cannot: properties in too-poor condition for bank financing, situations requiring faster closing than banks allow, or borrowers with unconventional income documentation. The speed and flexibility are the primary advantages despite higher costs.\n\nHard money lending is a subset of private money—institutional private lenders with standardized programs who lend based primarily on collateral LTV. Private money in its purest form involves networking with individual investors who directly fund deals.',
      example: 'Unable to get a conventional loan on the distressed property, the investor obtained a 12-month private money loan at 11% to acquire and renovate the building before refinancing into a conventional rental loan.',
      related: ['leverage', 'brrrr-method', 'cash-on-cash-return', 'due-diligence'],
