      letter: 'D',
      shortDef: 'The IRS tax on accumulated depreciation deductions taken during ownership, owed when a rental property is sold, at up to 25%.',
      fullDef: 'Depreciation recapture is the IRS mechanism for recovering the tax benefit of depreciation deductions when a rental property is sold at a gain. The portion of the gain attributable to previously claimed depreciation is taxed at a maximum rate of 25% (the unrecaptured Section 1250 gain rate)—higher than the long-term capital gains rate that applies to the remaining gain.\n\nFor example, if you claimed $50,000 in depreciation and sell at a $150,000 gain, the first $50,000 is recaptured at up to 25% ($12,500 in tax); the remaining $100,000 is taxed at your long-term capital gains rate. Your "adjusted basis" is reduced by accumulated depreciation, which effectively increases the taxable gain.\n\nA 1031 exchange defers both capital gains and recapture indefinitely; a stepped-up basis at death eliminates both. Depreciation recapture is frequently overlooked in return analysis and should be modeled in any planned exit.',
