      letter: 'O',
      shortDef: 'Medications available without a prescription—including analgesics, antihistamines, antacids, and decongestants—used to treat common symptoms.',
      fullDef: 'Over-the-counter (OTC) medications are drugs that the FDA has determined to be safe and effective for self-administration without physician oversight when used as directed. Common categories include: analgesics/antipyretics (acetaminophen, ibuprofen, naproxen), antihistamines (diphenhydramine, cetirizine, loratadine), antacids (calcium carbonate, famotidine), decongestants (pseudoephedrine, oxymetazoline), and topical antiseptics and corticosteroids.\n\nDespite being available without prescription, OTC medications carry real risks when misused. Acetaminophen overdose (intentional or cumulative) is the leading cause of acute liver failure in the US. NSAIDs (ibuprofen, naproxen) can cause gastric bleeding, renal impairment, and cardiovascular events, especially in older adults or those taking blood thinners. Antihistamines cause significant sedation and fall risk in the elderly.\n\nAlways read the label, check for drug interactions with prescription medications, follow dosing directions precisely, and inform your physician about regular OTC use. "OTC" does not mean "safe in any amount" or "safe for everyone."',
      example: 'The patient taking warfarin was advised to avoid ibuprofen for her headache—despite its OTC status, NSAIDs significantly increase bleeding risk when combined with anticoagulants.',
