      letter: 'M',
      shortDef: 'The smallest amount you must pay each month to keep your credit card account in good standing and avoid a late fee—but it maximizes interest costs.',
      fullDef: 'The minimum payment on a credit card is typically the greater of a flat dollar amount ($25–$35) or a percentage of the outstanding balance (usually 1–2%) plus any fees and interest charged. Making only the minimum payment avoids late fees and negative credit reporting but is an extremely expensive way to carry debt.\n\nAt a 20% APR on a $5,000 balance with a 2% minimum payment, it would take approximately 29 years to pay off the balance making only minimums—and you would pay over $7,000 in interest alone, more than the original balance. Credit card statements are now required by law (CARD Act of 2009) to show how long payoff takes at minimum payment and at a fixed payment that clears the balance in three years.\n\nMaking even a small additional payment above the minimum dramatically accelerates payoff. Paying $200/month instead of the $100 minimum on a $5,000 balance at 20% APR cuts payoff time from 29 years to about 3 years and saves over $6,000 in interest.',
      example: 'The statement showed that paying only the $97 monthly minimum would take 27 years and $6,800 in interest to clear the $3,200 balance—motivating the cardholder to commit to $250/month instead.',
      related: ['apr', 'credit-utilization', 'balance-transfer', 'grace-period'],
