      term: 'Overdraft Fee',
      slug: 'overdraft-fee',
      letter: 'O',
      shortDef: 'A fee charged by a bank when a transaction exceeds your available balance; typically $25–$35 per incident, or $0 with overdraft protection.',
      fullDef: 'An overdraft occurs when a transaction (debit purchase, check, ACH payment) exceeds the available balance in a checking account. Traditional banks charge $25–$35 per overdraft item, and multiple overdrafts in a single day can stack to $100+ in fees. Some banks also charge a "sustained overdraft fee" for each day the account remains negative.\n\nRegulatory changes have reshaped overdraft practices significantly. Banks must obtain opt-in consent before covering debit card and ATM transactions for a fee. If you have not opted in, those transactions are simply declined—often the preferable outcome. Linking a savings account or a line of credit as overdraft protection typically costs far less than a per-item fee.\n\nMany online and challenger banks (Chime, Current, Ally) now offer fee-free overdraft protection up to a limit, or simply decline transactions that would overdraw the account. Reviewing your bank\'s overdraft policy and switching to fee-free overdraft arrangements is low-effort and can save hundreds of dollars annually for people who occasionally run tight on funds.',
      example: 'After three overdraft fees totaling $105 in one month, the customer linked her savings account to her checking account as overdraft protection—paying $0 in future overdraft costs.',
      related: ['fdic-insurance', 'high-yield-savings', 'budget', 'fraud-protection'],
