      term: 'Door/Window Sensor',
      slug: 'door-window-sensor',
      letter: 'D',
      shortDef: 'A two-piece magnetic contact sensor that triggers an alarm when a door or window is opened, breaking the magnetic circuit between the two halves.',
      fullDef: 'Door and window sensors consist of two components: a magnet and a reed switch. When the door is closed, the magnet holds the reed switch in a closed (normal) circuit position. Opening the door separates the magnet from the switch, breaking the circuit and signaling the panel. This binary open/closed signal is the simplest and most reliable detection mechanism in home security.\n\nHardwired sensors, used in professionally installed systems, run a two-conductor wire back to the panel and cost $5–$20 per unit in materials plus $15–$30 labor. Wireless sensors use batteries (typically lasting 2–5 years) and communicate via 433 MHz, Z-Wave, Zigbee, or proprietary RF; they cost $15–$45 each. Recessed sensors are installed inside the door frame for a clean finish and are harder for an intruder to identify and defeat.\n\nA fully protected home typically needs 10–20 door/window sensors covering all entry points on the ground floor plus basement windows. At an average of $20–$30 per wireless sensor, the sensor hardware alone for a well-protected home runs $200–$600.',
      example: 'The installer equipped all 14 first-floor windows and both exterior doors with recessed sensors, totaling $340 in hardware — a $24/sensor average — before wiring them back to the hardwired control panel.',
      related: ['control-panel', 'glass-break-sensor', 'motion-sensor', 'diy-vs-professional-install'],
