      slug: 'doorbell-camera',
      letter: 'D',
      shortDef: 'A video camera integrated into a doorbell that records visitors, sends motion alerts to your smartphone, and enables two-way audio communication.',
      fullDef: 'Doorbell cameras have become the single most purchased home security device in the US. The Ring Video Doorbell (launched 2013) pioneered the category; as of 2024, Ring, Nest, and Arlo command over 80% of the market. They replace or supplement an existing doorbell wired circuit or operate on battery, and most stream 1080p–2K video to a companion app.\n\nKey features to compare: field of view (160° is standard; some offer 180° head-to-toe), night vision quality (color night vision requires ambient light; infrared night vision works in complete darkness), local vs. cloud storage options, package detection analytics, and integration with smart locks for delivery access. Battery-powered models need recharging every 1–6 months depending on activity volume.\n\nHardwired doorbell cameras cost $100–$250 for the device; battery models $80–$230. Cloud recording subscriptions typically run $3–$10/month per camera. Wired installation is straightforward but requires 16–24V AC transformer power at the existing chime; some older homes need a transformer upgrade ($20–$60 in parts).',
      example: 'After installing a $179 wired doorbell camera with a $5/month cloud plan, the homeowner captured footage of a porch pirate, submitted it to police, and had the package thief identified within 48 hours.',
