      fullDef: 'Smart locks replace or augment a traditional deadbolt with motorized actuation controlled by Bluetooth, Z-Wave, Zigbee, or Wi-Fi. Most models retain a physical key cylinder as a backup. The primary value propositions are keyless entry (codes, fingerprint, NFC card), remote locking and unlocking from anywhere with a Wi-Fi or hub connection, and temporary or time-limited access codes for guests, cleaners, or contractors.\n\nIntegration with security systems enables rules like "lock automatically when alarm is armed away" or "trigger an alert if the door is unlocked after midnight." Integration with smart home platforms (Amazon Alexa, Google Home, Apple HomeKit, SmartThings) allows voice control and automation. Z-Wave models require a compatible hub (such as a SmartThings hub or Ring Alarm panel) but offer the most reliable mesh network range.\n\nSmart locks cost $100–$300 for the device. Installation is DIY-friendly (30–45 minutes with a screwdriver) on standard US single-cylinder deadbolt prep holes. Monthly cloud subscription fees are rare for locks — access history, code management, and remote control are typically included in the free app.',
      example: 'The homeowner programmed a temporary 6-digit code for a housecleaner that automatically expired after each Thursday visit, eliminating the need to exchange physical keys and providing a remote-access log.',
