      shortDef: 'A wall-mounted input device used to arm, disarm, and control a security system by entering a numeric PIN or using a touchscreen interface.',
      fullDef: 'The keypad is the primary user interface for a security system. Entry-level keypads use a numeric matrix with LED or LCD status indicators. Premium touchscreen keypads offer a graphical interface showing zone status, event history, and camera thumbnails. Keypads communicate with the control panel via wiring (for hardwired systems) or encrypted RF (for wireless systems).\n\nPIN length and complexity matter for security: 4-digit codes allow 10,000 combinations but are vulnerable to shoulder surfing; 6-digit codes offer 1,000,000 combinations. Most systems support multiple user codes — typically 32–100 — each with configurable access levels and schedules. A "duress code" (one digit off from the real code) silently alerts the monitoring center while appearing to disarm the system normally.\n\nPlacement is critical: the primary keypad should be within arm\'s reach of the main entry door to allow disarming within the entry delay period (typically 30–60 seconds). Secondary keypads in master bedrooms enable one-touch panic and arm/disarm without walking to the front door. Keypads cost $30–$100 each for hardwired models; wireless versions run $60–$150.',
