      shortDef: 'A configuration where alarm alerts are sent directly to the homeowner\'s smartphone instead of to a professional monitoring center, making the homeowner responsible for calling emergency services.',
      fullDef: 'Self-monitoring eliminates the monthly monitoring fee by routing all alerts — alarm triggers, low battery warnings, sensor faults — directly to the owner\'s smartphone via push notification or SMS. The homeowner then decides whether to call 911 or dismiss the alert. Systems like Ring Alarm, SimpliSafe, and Abode work equally well in self-monitored mode with no subscription required.\n\nThe primary limitation is response lag: a homeowner awakened by an alert at 2 a.m. may take 2–5 minutes to process the notification, confirm it is not a false alarm, and call 911 — versus 45 seconds for a professional center. If the homeowner is traveling or the phone is on silent, the alert may be missed entirely. For this reason, self-monitoring is most appropriate for low-risk situations (cabin, vacation property, lower-crime areas) or as a supplement to professional monitoring.\n\nSelf-monitoring saves $120–$600/year in subscription fees. A hybrid approach — self-monitoring with professional monitoring as an on-demand upgrade via apps like Noonlight or the Ring Protect Pro plan — provides flexibility without a long-term contract.',
      example: 'The homeowner self-monitored a vacation cabin, receiving instant door sensor alerts on his phone and accepting the tradeoff that police response would be slower than at his primary residence with professional monitoring.',
