      shortDef: 'A secondary communication path that uses a cellular radio built into the security panel to maintain the monitoring connection if the internet or landline is cut.',
      fullDef: 'Cellular backup is the most critical redundancy feature in a monitored security system. Most burglars who disable home security start by cutting the phone line or the internet cable at the network interface box outside the home. A system that communicates only via broadband goes dark the moment the cable is cut. A panel with a built-in cellular radio (LTE or 4G) maintains its monitoring link through the cell network independently of any wiring outside the home.\n\nCellular communicators use dedicated machine-to-machine SIM cards on major carrier networks (AT&T, T-Mobile, Verizon) managed by the monitoring company — homeowners do not need to add a line to their personal plan. The latency is comparable to broadband: alarm signals typically reach the monitoring center within 10–30 seconds over cellular.\n\nMost modern DIY systems (Ring Alarm, SimpliSafe, ADT) include cellular communication built into the base station. For older hardwired panels, cellular communicators can be added as modules costing $60–$150 in hardware; the monthly monitoring plan usually includes the cellular connection. Systems that rely solely on broadband without cellular backup do not qualify for the UL Listed Central Station standard.',
      example: 'A burglar cut the cable at the utility entrance before breaking the rear window; the cellular-enabled panel transmitted the alarm to the monitoring center within 12 seconds via T-Mobile LTE, and police were dispatched before the intruder reached the bedroom.',
