      letter: 'L',
      shortDef: 'Two older communication paths for security panels: POTS (plain old telephone service) landline and internet/broadband — both now superseded by cellular as the preferred primary or backup path.',
      fullDef: 'POTS (plain old telephone service) landline was the standard monitoring communication method from the 1970s through the early 2000s. The panel would dial the monitoring center\'s receiving equipment over the copper phone network when an alarm fired. POTS lines are increasingly rare — fewer than 30% of US households had a landline as of 2024 — and many phone companies have or will be discontinuing copper POTS service entirely.\n\nBroadband (internet) communication replaced landlines for many systems in the 2010s, offering faster signal transmission, two-way communication for remote control, and integration with cloud video. However, broadband communicators require a working router and internet service and can be defeated by cutting the cable at the outside utility box.\n\nCellular is now the gold standard because it is independent of all in-home wiring. The best practice is cellular primary + broadband backup (or cellular only) rather than the legacy approach of broadband primary + cellular backup. UL-listed centers require the monitoring connection to meet specific uptime standards that typically can only be achieved with cellular.',
