      shortDef: 'A monitoring facility that has been inspected and certified by Underwriters Laboratories to meet strict standards for staffing, redundancy, response time, and physical security.',
      fullDef: 'Underwriters Laboratories (UL) issues two central station certifications: UL Listed (the standard) and UL Listed — Level AA (the highest grade). To achieve listing, a monitoring center must pass an on-site audit covering physical construction (reinforced structure capable of withstanding high winds or seismic events), power redundancy (72-hour backup generator plus UPS), staffing requirements, average signal response time, alarm handling procedures, and record retention.\n\nThe CSAA (Central Station Alarm Association) Five Diamond certification is a parallel industry standard that layers training requirements on top of the UL physical standards. Many top-tier centers hold both. ADT, Brinks, Alarm.com, and similar companies operate their own UL-listed centers; many smaller dealers use third-party wholesale monitoring companies that are also UL-listed.\n\nWhy it matters: UL listing often qualifies your monitoring contract for the homeowner\'s insurance discount (5–20% off the security portion of your premium). Some municipalities also give higher police dispatch priority to alarm signals from UL-listed centers versus non-listed monitoring services.',
      example: 'The homeowner\'s insurer required proof of a UL-listed monitoring contract to apply the 15% security discount on their homeowner\'s policy — saving $180/year against a $25/month monitoring plan.',
