      term: 'Response Time',
      slug: 'response-time',
      letter: 'R',
      shortDef: 'The elapsed time from when an alarm signal reaches a monitoring center to when an operator calls the homeowner or dispatches emergency services.',
      fullDef: 'Response time is measured in two segments: signal transmission time (from the panel to the monitoring center, typically 5–30 seconds over cellular) and operator handling time (from signal receipt to first call or dispatch). UL standards and CSAA guidelines set target operator response times of under 90 seconds; top-rated centers achieve under 45 seconds on average.\n\nPractical police response time — from dispatch to arrival — averages 7–10 minutes nationally in urban and suburban areas, and 15–45 minutes in rural areas. This means the total time from an alarm trigger to police arrival is typically 8–12 minutes in suburbs, even with the fastest monitoring response. An intruder\'s average time inside a home during a burglary is 8–10 minutes, making monitoring response speed a real variable in whether a crime is interrupted.\n\nVideo verification dramatically improves both response time and dispatch priority. When a monitoring operator can view camera footage and confirm a person is present, they escalate the dispatch to an active crime versus a possible false alarm, and many municipalities give these calls faster patrol response.',
