      term: 'False Alarm Fine',
      slug: 'false-alarm-fine',
      letter: 'F',
      shortDef: 'A municipal fee charged to a homeowner when police respond to a security alarm that turns out to be accidental, typically starting after 1–3 free responses per year.',
      fullDef: 'False alarms account for 94–99% of all alarm dispatches according to the Security Industry Alarm Coalition (SIAC). To reduce unnecessary police resource expenditure, virtually every major US city and county has implemented a false alarm ordinance. Most allow 1–3 free responses per calendar year; subsequent false alarms trigger fines that escalate with frequency — commonly $50–$100 for the first paid offense, $100–$200 for the second, and $200–$500 or more for repeat offenders.\n\nAlarm permits are required in most jurisdictions before a monitored system can be legally dispatched; permit fees run $15–$50/year. Failure to register can double the false alarm fines. Some cities have moved to "verified response" policies — police will not dispatch until the monitoring center provides video or audio verification of an actual crime in progress.\n\nThe most common causes of false alarms: user error (forgetting to disarm within the entry delay), low sensor batteries, improperly mounted door sensors that rattle, spider webs across motion sensor lenses, and pets. A consistent false alarm problem should prompt an audit of sensor placement and sensitivity settings before fines accumulate.',
