      term: '433 MHz Frequency',
      slug: '433mhz-frequency',
      letter: '4',
      shortDef: 'A radio frequency used by many older and budget home security sensors to transmit open/close and alarm signals to the control panel without requiring a mesh network infrastructure.',
      fullDef: '433 MHz is an unlicensed ISM (industrial, scientific, medical) band used by a wide range of consumer wireless devices including basic security sensors, garage door openers, weather stations, and remote controls. Security systems using 433 MHz are typically one-way (sensor transmits to panel; panel cannot query sensor state on demand), use basic amplitude shift keying or frequency shift keying modulation, and offer minimal inherent encryption.\n\nThe advantage of 433 MHz sensors is cost and battery life: a single CR2032 coin cell can last 3–5 years in a basic door sensor at this frequency. The disadvantages are vulnerability to jamming (a cheap $30 RF jammer can block 433 MHz signals, theoretically blinding the panel) and the lack of bidirectional communication that enables supervision (knowing if a sensor\'s battery is low or the device has gone offline).\n\nModern premium systems have moved to encrypted, supervised protocols (Z-Wave, Zigbee, or proprietary like SimpliSafe\'s 433 MHz with rolling-code encryption). Alarm.com and other professional platforms explicitly prohibit use of un-encrypted 433 MHz sensors. For high-security applications, supervised Z-Wave or 900 MHz bidirectional protocols are strongly preferred.',
      example: 'A security researcher demonstrated that a $30 handheld RF jammer could block alarm signals from a budget 433 MHz system, causing the panel to never receive the door-open event — an illustration of why encrypted, supervised protocols matter in higher-risk homes.',
      related: ['z-wave-vs-zigbee', 'control-panel', 'end-to-end-encryption', 'cellular-backup'],
