      slug: 'video-retention',
      letter: 'V',
      shortDef: 'The number of days that recorded video is stored before being automatically overwritten; determined by storage capacity, camera resolution, and compression settings.',
      fullDef: 'Video retention is the practical storage window available before footage is overwritten. Calculating it requires knowing: storage capacity (in TB), number of cameras, average bitrate per camera, and whether recording is continuous or motion-triggered. A common rule of thumb for continuous 1080p H.264 recording at standard bitrate: approximately 20–25 GB per camera per day, meaning 1 TB stores about 40–50 camera-days.\n\nA 4-camera system with a 2 TB NVR gets approximately 10–12 days of continuous 1080p retention. Upgrading to a 4 TB drive extends this to 20–25 days. Switching to H.265 compression (same quality, ~50% smaller file size) doubles effective retention without a hardware change. Motion-only recording can extend retention by 3–5x compared to continuous recording in low-activity environments.\n\nFor most residential purposes, 14–30 days of retention is the standard target — enough to catch crimes not discovered immediately (package theft, vandalism) and to respond to police requests for evidence. Insurance claims for theft or vandalism sometimes require footage from several days before the discovery date, making at least 30-day retention advisable.',
      example: 'After configuring H.265 encoding on the NVR and switching to motion-triggered recording, the homeowner increased effective retention from 11 days to 38 days on the same 2 TB drive without adding hardware.',
