      term: 'AI Detection vs Motion Zones',
      slug: 'ai-detection-vs-motion-zones',
      letter: 'A',
      shortDef: 'AI detection uses machine learning to classify objects (person, vehicle, animal) before triggering an alert; motion zones define a pixel-based area in the frame where any motion will trigger recording.',
      fullDef: 'Traditional motion detection in cameras works at the pixel level: when enough pixels change between consecutive frames, the camera registers motion and starts recording or sends an alert. The problem is that swaying trees, passing headlights, blowing leaves, and rain all trigger pixel-level motion, generating overwhelming false notifications.\n\nAI-based object detection uses a trained neural network — either running on a local processor chip in the camera or in the cloud — to classify what triggered the motion event before sending a notification. Person detection (the most common) specifically looks for human silhouettes using pose estimation and shape analysis. Vehicle detection, package detection, and facial recognition are offered by higher-tier services. AI detection reduces actionable false alerts by 70–90% compared to raw pixel motion detection.\n\nMotion zones are a complementary tool: a user draws a polygon in the camera\'s app to define the area of interest (the front door, not the street), so that motion outside the zone is ignored entirely. Using both AI detection and motion zones together provides the lowest false alert rate. AI detection is offered free by Eufy, Reolink, and others with on-camera processing chips; Arlo and Ring charge for it as part of a paid subscription.',
      example: 'After enabling both person detection AI and a motion zone covering only the front porch (excluding the street), the homeowner\'s doorbell camera dropped from 45 alerts per day to 3–5 meaningful person-detected alerts.',
      related: ['motion-sensor', 'ip-vs-analog-camera', 'video-retention', 'doorbell-camera'],
