      shortDef: 'DIY security systems are self-installed by the homeowner using wireless plug-and-play components; professionally installed systems are wired and configured by a certified technician.',
      fullDef: 'DIY security systems have captured a dominant share of new residential security installations since 2018. Systems like Ring Alarm, SimpliSafe, and Abode ship complete kits with adhesive-mounted wireless sensors, a cellular panel, and a companion app that walks through setup. A typical 5-piece starter kit installs in 30–60 minutes with no tools. DIY systems cost $200–$600 in hardware; monthly monitoring (optional) runs $10–$25/month.\n\nProfessional installation involves a licensed alarm technician running Cat5e or 22/4 wire to hardwired sensors, mounting motion detectors at optimal heights, programming zone names and response types, and commissioning the system with the monitoring center. Hardwired systems offer higher reliability (no batteries in most sensors, supervised wiring) and cleaner aesthetics. Professional installation adds $150–$600 in labor to a job that already includes $500–$1,500+ in hardware.\n\nThe main reasons to choose professional installation: high-end NVR camera systems that require network and mounting expertise, integration with access control, homes with brick or masonry construction where wireless signals are attenuated, and multi-zone complex layouts where proper sensor placement requires experience. For most standard single-family homes, DIY systems offer 80–90% of the protection at 40–50% of the total cost.',
