      fullDef: 'Alarm permits are required in the majority of US cities and counties for any monitored security system that has access to police dispatch. The permit process typically involves submitting contact information, site address, a list of keyholders for verification calls, and paying a nominal annual fee ($15–$75). Without a permit, police departments in many jurisdictions may refuse to respond to alarm dispatches or impose enhanced false alarm fines.\n\nSome monitoring companies handle permit applications on behalf of new customers as part of their onboarding process. Others provide the forms and instructions but leave the filing to the homeowner. Permits must be renewed annually in most jurisdictions; forgotten renewals can quietly lapse while the monitoring system continues to operate.\n\nPermit databases are increasingly used by monitoring centers to route dispatch through the appropriate police precinct and to track false alarm histories per address. An address flagged for multiple false alarms may require verified response (video or audio confirmation) before police will respond, regardless of permit status.',
