      fullDef: 'An LLC (Limited Liability Company) is a state-chartered business entity that provides its owners (called members) with personal liability protection: the members\' personal assets are generally not reachable by business creditors or judgments against the LLC. Unlike a corporation, an LLC does not have shareholders, a board of directors, or formal meeting requirements — governance is governed by an operating agreement.\n\nFor federal tax purposes, a single-member LLC is treated as a disregarded entity (reported on Schedule C of the member\'s 1040) by default. A multi-member LLC is taxed as a partnership by default. Either type can elect corporate taxation (S-corp or C-corp) by filing the appropriate IRS forms, which can provide payroll tax savings for profitable businesses when the owners are taking significant distributions.\n\nForming an LLC requires filing articles of organization with the state (cost: $50–$500 depending on state; Delaware is $90, California is $70 filing fee plus an $800/year minimum franchise tax) and maintaining a registered agent. Some states (California, New York) impose annual franchise taxes or publication requirements that add significant ongoing cost. A properly drafted operating agreement is essential to protect members\' interests and prevent default state rules from applying.',
      example: 'A freelance software developer formed a single-member LLC in Wyoming ($100 filing fee, no state income tax) to hold a growing SaaS business, separating her personal finances from business contracts and enabling S-corp tax election once net profit exceeded $80,000/year.',
