      shortDef: 'A tax election available to qualifying corporations or LLCs that allows business profits to pass through to shareholders\' personal returns while enabling payroll tax savings through reasonable-salary-plus-distribution structuring.',
      fullDef: 'An S-corporation is a tax designation elected by filing IRS Form 2553, not a separate business entity type. Both a C-corp and a qualifying LLC can elect S-corp taxation. The key benefit is payroll tax savings: while all self-employment income in a sole proprietorship or default LLC is subject to 15.3% self-employment tax (Social Security + Medicare) up to the Social Security wage base ($168,600 in 2024), an S-corp allows the owner-employee to split income between a "reasonable salary" (subject to payroll taxes) and a distribution (not subject to payroll taxes).\n\nFor a business generating $200,000 in net profit, an owner might take a $100,000 salary (with $15,300 in combined payroll taxes) and $100,000 in distributions (no payroll tax) — saving approximately $7,650/year versus taking all income as self-employment income. The IRS requires the salary to be "reasonable compensation" for the services performed; underpaying to minimize payroll taxes is an audit red flag.\n\nS-corp restrictions include: maximum 100 shareholders, all shareholders must be US citizens or permanent residents, only one class of stock is permitted, and no non-resident alien shareholders. These restrictions make S-corps unsuitable for venture-backed startups (which need convertible preferred stock) but appropriate for profitable service businesses with a small number of US-based owners.',
      example: 'A two-person accounting firm operating as an LLC elected S-corp status; each partner took $85,000 in salary and $60,000 in distributions, saving approximately $9,180/year in combined payroll taxes ($4,590 each) compared to taking all income as self-employment income.',
