      fullDef: 'A C-corporation (C-corp) is the default corporate entity taxed at the corporate level (21% federal rate since the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017) and then again at the shareholder level on dividends — the "double taxation" critique. However, for venture-backed startups, the C-corp is the only viable entity structure: VC investors require preferred stock with liquidation preferences, protective provisions, and anti-dilution rights that are incompatible with S-corp rules (one class of stock requirement) and operationally awkward in LLC structures.\n\nDelaware C-corps are the standard for venture-backed startups because Delaware\'s Court of Chancery has a well-developed body of corporate law, most institutional investors have investment documents drafted for Delaware entities, and the Delaware General Corporation Law provides maximum flexibility in designing stock classes and governance provisions. Incorporating in Delaware costs $89 + $50 for expedited filing; ongoing costs include a Delaware franchise tax (minimum $175/year for small companies, calculated on authorized shares or assumed par value).\n\nKey tax advantage for early investors: Qualified Small Business Stock (QSBS) under IRC Section 1202 allows investors in qualifying C-corps to exclude up to $10 million in capital gains (or 10× adjusted basis, whichever is greater) from federal tax if they hold the stock for 5+ years, the company\'s aggregate gross assets were under $50 million at issuance, and certain active business requirements are met.',
      example: 'A SaaS startup incorporated in Delaware as a C-corp before its seed round; the QSBS exclusion meant that seed investors who invested $500,000 and held for 5+ years could exclude up to $5 million in gains (10× basis) from federal capital gains tax entirely.',
