      fullDef: 'A sole proprietorship is the default business structure when an individual conducts business without forming any legal entity. No registration is required (though a DBA — "doing business as" — may be registered locally for a few dollars to use a trade name), and there is no distinction between the business and the owner for tax or liability purposes. All business income is reported on Schedule C of the owner\'s personal tax return and is subject to both income tax and 15.3% self-employment tax on net earnings.\n\nThe primary disadvantage is unlimited personal liability: business creditors can pursue the owner\'s personal bank accounts, home equity, vehicles, and savings. A single lawsuit or unpaid business debt can result in personal bankruptcy. This is why most attorneys advise forming an LLC before taking on clients, employees, or contracts with meaningful financial exposure.\n\nSole proprietorship works as a temporary starting point for testing a business concept with minimal cost but should be upgraded to an LLC as soon as the business has any meaningful revenue, contracts, or liability exposure. The incremental cost of LLC formation ($50–$500 in most states) is trivially small compared to the liability protection it provides.',
