      fullDef: 'An operating agreement is the LLC equivalent of a corporation\'s bylaws combined with a shareholder agreement. While not required in every state (only California, Delaware, Maine, Missouri, and New York mandate it), it is essential for every multi-member LLC and strongly advisable for single-member LLCs. Without an operating agreement, the default rules of the state\'s LLC statute govern the business — which are often inappropriate for the specific situation.\n\nKey provisions include: member ownership percentages (capital accounts), profit and loss allocation (can differ from ownership percentage if structured properly), distribution rights and timing, management structure (member-managed vs. manager-managed), voting thresholds for major decisions (supermajority for accepting new members, dissolving the company, selling assets), buy-sell provisions (right of first refusal, forced buy-sell on death or disability), and restrictions on transferring membership interests.\n\nDrafting a comprehensive operating agreement typically costs $1,500–$5,000 in attorney fees depending on complexity. The investment is worth making: a poorly drafted or absent operating agreement is one of the primary causes of co-founder disputes and LLC dissolution proceedings. Courts in several states have also held that LLCs without operating agreements or with inadequate operating agreements can lose their liability protection under veil-piercing theories.',
