      fullDef: 'Articles of incorporation (called a "certificate of incorporation" in Delaware) are the primary constitutional document of a corporation, filed with the secretary of state to legally bring the entity into existence. They typically include: the corporation\'s legal name, the state of incorporation, the registered agent\'s name and address, the number and classes of authorized shares (with par value), and the purpose of the corporation (which is usually stated as "any lawful purpose" in modern charters).\n\nFor a startup Delaware C-corp, the articles of incorporation are usually a one- to two-page document with 10 million authorized common shares at $0.0001 par value (total authorized capital = $1,000, resulting in a minimal Delaware franchise tax calculation). Incorporation in Delaware via a formation service (Stripe Atlas, Clerky, Firstbase) typically costs $500–$1,000 in service fees plus state fees, and produces both the certificate of incorporation and a standard board-approved initial capitalization and officer election.\n\nAmending the articles of incorporation — to authorize additional shares for an equity round, create preferred stock classes, or change the company name — requires board approval, stockholder approval (usually a majority), and filing an amended certificate with the state. Each preferred stock round (Series Seed, Series A) typically requires an amended certificate authorizing the new preferred class.',
      example: 'When raising its Series A at a $12 million pre-money valuation, the startup filed an amended certificate of incorporation in Delaware authorizing 5 million new Series A Preferred shares with a 1× non-participating liquidation preference and standard VC protective provisions, at a state filing cost of $89.',
