      fullDef: 'Every LLC and corporation is required to designate a registered agent (also called a statutory agent or agent for service of process) in the state where it is incorporated. The registered agent receives service of process (lawsuits), official government correspondence, tax notices, and annual report reminders at a physical address during business hours. The agent\'s name and address are part of the public record.\n\nFounders can serve as their own registered agent if they have a physical address in the state of incorporation. However, this is generally inadvisable for several reasons: you become publicly identified with legal service (your home address may appear in legal filings), you must be physically present at that address during business hours, and if you are away when a legal complaint is served and miss a response deadline, a default judgment can be entered against your company.\n\nProfessional registered agent services cost $50–$300/year and provide an address in virtually every state, keep you off public records, and send timely electronic notifications for any legal or government correspondence. Services like Northwest Registered Agent, Legalzoom, and CT Corporation serve millions of businesses. For companies incorporated in one state but operating in another, you need a registered agent in each state where you are "qualified to do business" (a registration requirement triggered by having employees, offices, or significant business activity in that state).',
