      fullDef: 'An Employer Identification Number (EIN), also called a Federal Tax Identification Number, is the business equivalent of a Social Security Number. The IRS assigns a unique 9-digit EIN to every business entity (LLC, corporation, partnership) and to sole proprietors who hire employees. Even single-member LLCs with no employees should obtain an EIN to keep business and personal finances separate and to open a business bank account without using a personal SSN.\n\nApplying for an EIN is free and can be done online through the IRS website at irs.gov/ein in approximately 5 minutes; the EIN is issued instantly during the online session. International applicants without an SSN must apply by phone or fax (Form SS-4). One EIN application per day per responsible party is permitted through the online system.\n\nThe EIN is required for: opening a business bank account (all US banks require it), filing federal business tax returns (Form 1065, 1120, 1120-S), applying for business licenses, hiring employees (payroll tax accounts), obtaining business credit, setting up retirement plans (SEP-IRA, Solo 401(k)), and applying for SBA loans. After entity formation, obtaining the EIN should be the immediate second step.',
