      fullDef: 'Bootstrapping refers to funding a startup entirely from the founder\'s own resources — personal savings, initial sales revenue, and profit reinvestment — without equity investors or debt financing. The term comes from the idiom "pulling oneself up by one\'s bootstraps." Famous bootstrapped successes include Mailchimp ($800M acquisition by Intuit in 2021 after 20 years without outside investment), Basecamp, Craigslist, and TechSmith.\n\nThe primary advantages are full ownership (no dilution), complete strategic control (no investor board seats or approval requirements), and forced capital efficiency. Bootstrapped founders must generate revenue early and build sustainable unit economics, which often creates healthier long-term business models than VC-funded companies that can mask inefficiency with capital.\n\nThe limitations are slower growth (constrained by cash flow), inability to compete in winner-take-all markets requiring rapid scale, and personal financial risk. The median bootstrapped startup generates $300,000–$2M in annual revenue — sufficient for comfortable founder income but rarely building a billion-dollar company. For businesses in SaaS, content, professional services, e-commerce, and niche B2B markets, bootstrapping is a viable and often optimal path.',
