      fullDef: 'Angel investors are individual accredited investors (income $200,000+/year or net worth $1M+ excluding primary residence under SEC rules) who deploy personal capital into early-stage companies. They typically invest $25,000–$500,000 in a single company at the pre-seed or seed stage, when institutional venture capital is too early. Angel investing is high-risk: research consistently shows that a small fraction of angel deals drive all returns, with the top 5–10% of investments generating 3–5× while the majority return little or nothing.\n\nAngels provide more than capital: successful angels with domain expertise, founder networks, and exit experience are often the most valuable early advisors. The best angels can open doors to customer relationships, talent, and later-stage VCs. AngelList estimates that over 60,000 active angel investors exist in the US, though true active angels (deploying capital in 3+ deals/year) number around 15,000–20,000.\n\nAngels typically invest via convertible notes or SAFE agreements at the pre-seed stage, and via priced equity rounds at seed. Check sizes and deal terms are more negotiable than with institutional VCs. The average angel investment period before exit is 5–7 years; internal rates of return across a portfolio of 10+ angel investments typically range from -100% (total loss) to 25%+ for skilled investors with deal flow advantages.',
