      fullDef: 'Venture capital (VC) firms raise funds from limited partners (LPs) — pension funds, university endowments, family offices, fund-of-funds — and deploy that capital into early-to-growth-stage companies in exchange for equity. VC firms typically manage funds of $50M–$1B+, with a 10-year fund life. The fund management fee is 2%/year of committed capital; the carry (performance fee) is 20% of profits above the hurdle rate — hence "2 and 20."\n\nVC returns follow a power law: 65% of VC investments return less than the invested capital; 20% return 1–5×; 10% return 5–20×; and 5% or fewer generate 20–100× returns. A single exceptional investment can return an entire fund. This power law dynamic drives VCs to seek "venture-scale" opportunities — companies targeting $1B+ TAMs with the potential to become a fund-returning investment.\n\nThe Series A benchmark as of 2024: $2–$5M ARR with strong growth (80–120% year-over-year), product-market fit evidence (low churn, NPS 40+), a capital-efficient CAC:LTV ratio above 3:1, and a clear path to $50–$100M ARR. Median Series A deal size in 2023 was $12M at a $40M pre-money valuation per PitchBook data.',
