      fullDef: 'A seed round is generally the first institutional funding event for a startup, though it may follow a pre-seed angel round. In 2023, median seed round size in the US was $3M, with a pre-money valuation of $10–$15M (implying 20–25% dilution). Seed investors are typically seed-specific funds ($50M–$200M in AUM), multi-stage VC firms writing small initial checks, angel syndicates, and high-net-worth individuals.\n\nThe typical use of proceeds at seed: 60–70% for technical talent (1–3 engineers plus any technical co-founders upgrading from part-time), 15–25% for product and infrastructure costs (AWS, Stripe, tooling), 10–15% for go-to-market experimentation. The 18-month runway target from seed is a commonly cited standard: sufficient runway to reach the ARR and growth milestones (typically $1.5–$3M ARR) needed to raise a Series A at improved valuation.\n\nSeed rounds are frequently structured as SAFE notes or convertible notes that convert to equity at the next priced round, avoiding the legal cost and complexity of a full priced equity round at an early stage. A priced seed round (issuing actual preferred stock) is more common when the round is large ($3M+) or when sophisticated institutional investors require it.',
