      fullDef: 'A Series A is the first round in which institutional venture capital typically leads a priced equity round, issuing Series A Preferred shares with defined rights including: liquidation preference (1× non-participating is standard), anti-dilution protection (typically weighted-average broad-based), board representation (the lead VC typically receives one board seat), information rights, and pro-rata rights in future rounds.\n\nSeries A diligence has intensified since 2021: teams now typically spend 3–6 months in process, with the lead VC conducting 50–100 customer reference calls, detailed financial model reviews, competitive landscape analysis, and technical due diligence. The average time from first meeting to term sheet at top-tier VCs is 8–12 weeks; process completion and wire transfer takes another 4–8 weeks. Total legal costs for both sides (incorporating updated certificate, stockholder agreements, and investor documents) run $50,000–$100,000.\n\nPost-Series A, startups typically have 18–24 months of runway and a mandate to grow from $2–5M ARR to $8–15M ARR — the range needed to justify a Series B at a higher multiple. Failure to hit ARR targets in this window often leads to an "inside round" (existing investors bridge at flat or down valuation) or shutdown.',
