      fullDef: 'A convertible note is a loan to a startup that automatically converts into equity at the company\'s next qualified financing round. Unlike SAFE notes, convertible notes accrue interest (typically 5–8% annually) and have a maturity date (usually 12–24 months), after which the outstanding principal and interest either convert or become due as debt — creating pressure to close the next round before maturity.\n\nConvertible notes include two primary investor-protective provisions: a discount rate (typically 15–25%) that allows note holders to convert at a lower per-share price than new investors in the next round, and a valuation cap that sets a maximum company valuation for conversion purposes. If the company raises a Series A at $20M pre-money but the note has a $6M cap, the note holder converts as if the price were based on $6M — dramatically increasing their share count.\n\nConvertible notes have largely been replaced by SAFE agreements for pre-seed and seed rounds because SAFEs have no interest accrual, no maturity date, and simpler terms. However, convertible notes remain common in bridge financing situations (existing investors bridging between rounds) and in markets where foreign investors prefer debt instruments over equity for regulatory reasons.',
      example: 'An angel invested $200,000 via a convertible note at 6% interest, 20% discount, and $5M cap; 15 months later at Series A ($18M pre-money), the principal plus accrued interest ($215,000) converted at the $5M cap price per share, yielding 3.6× more shares than a new Series A investor paying the same $215,000 at the actual round price.',
