      fullDef: 'The SAFE (Simple Agreement for Future Equity) was created by Y Combinator in 2013 to simplify early-stage fundraising. Unlike a convertible note, a SAFE is not debt — it has no interest rate, no maturity date, and no repayment obligation if the company fails. Investors receive the right to convert their SAFE into the next class of equity issued in a priced round, at terms defined in the SAFE.\n\nThe two most common SAFE variants are: post-money SAFE with valuation cap (the standard YC form since 2018, which makes dilution calculation transparent — a $200K SAFE on a $4M post-money cap owns exactly 5% of the company after conversion) and pre-money SAFE with cap and discount (the earlier format, where dilution depended on the full round size and cap table structure). YC\'s post-money SAFE form is freely downloadable and has been used in hundreds of thousands of seed financings.\n\nSAFEs converted in later rounds are treated as the lowest tranche of preferred stock or as a separate class (often called SAFE Preferred). Multiple SAFEs at different cap levels result in complex waterfall calculations at exit — the "SAFE stack" problem that sophisticated founders model carefully before issuing too many SAFEs at different terms.',
      example: 'A pre-revenue startup raised $1.5M across 6 SAFEs using the standard YC post-money form at a $6M valuation cap; each investor could calculate exactly their ownership at conversion — the largest check ($500K) owned 8.33% ($500K/$6M) of the company immediately post-conversion at Series A.',
