      fullDef: 'A valuation cap is the investor-protective mechanism in SAFE and convertible note instruments that limits the price at which early capital converts to equity. If a company raises a $500K SAFE at a $4M valuation cap and later raises a Series A at a $20M pre-money valuation, the SAFE converts as if the company were worth $4M — giving the SAFE investor shares at 1/5th the price of Series A investors. Without a cap, early investors\' capital converts at the same price as new money, eliminating any premium for early-stage risk.\n\nCap-setting is one of the most important negotiations in early fundraising. Set the cap too low and founders give away substantial ownership to early investors; set it too high and the cap provides little protection and the round may be unattractive to investors. Common pre-seed valuation caps range from $3M–$8M for pre-revenue startups; seed caps range from $6M–$20M depending on traction and market conditions.\n\nIn the post-money SAFE structure (YC standard), the valuation cap equals the post-money valuation used for the conversion math, making ownership calculations deterministic: $200K at a $4M post-money cap = exactly 5% of the cap table after conversion, regardless of how many other SAFEs are outstanding. In pre-money SAFE or convertible note structures, the dilution calculation depends on all other instruments in the cap table, creating ambiguity.',
