      shortDef: 'The reduction in a shareholder\'s ownership percentage that occurs when new shares are issued to investors, employees (via option pool), or upon conversion of SAFEs or convertible notes.',
      fullDef: 'Dilution is the mathematical reduction in each existing shareholder\'s percentage ownership that results from issuing new shares. If a founder owns 5,000,000 shares out of 10,000,000 total outstanding (50% ownership) and the company issues 2,500,000 new shares to an investor, the founder now owns 5,000,000 of 12,500,000 shares (40% ownership) — a 10-percentage-point dilution or 20% reduction in relative ownership.\n\nThe major dilution events in a startup\'s lifecycle: (1) co-founder equity splits (initial issuance), (2) option pool creation (typically 10–20% of the fully diluted cap table at seed, diluting existing holders), (3) each equity financing round (seed, Series A, B, etc.), (4) SAFE and convertible note conversions, and (5) secondary sales or employee stock issuance. Tracking dilution through a "dilution waterfall" model is essential for understanding the economic value remaining at each exit scenario.\n\nThe anti-dilution provision in preferred stock protects investors from dilution in down rounds (new shares issued at a lower price per share than the investor paid). Broad-based weighted-average anti-dilution is the standard, investor-friendly but founder-tolerable form; full-ratchet anti-dilution (which reprices the investor\'s entire holding to the down-round price) is investor-friendly but highly punitive to founders and other shareholders.',
