      shortDef: 'The monthly rate at which a startup spends cash; gross burn is total monthly cash outflow, net burn is the shortfall after revenue, and both are central to forecasting runway.',
      fullDef: 'Burn rate quantifies how fast a company is consuming cash. Gross burn is the total monthly cash expenditure (salaries, rent, infrastructure, marketing, legal, etc.) regardless of revenue. Net burn is gross burn minus monthly revenue — the actual monthly reduction in cash balance. A company spending $200,000/month with $80,000 in revenue has a $120,000/month net burn.\n\nBurn rate is used to calculate runway (months of cash remaining = cash on hand ÷ net burn). Investors evaluate burn relative to the growth being generated: a $150,000/month net burn that is growing ARR from $500K to $2M in 12 months is highly efficient; the same burn rate growing ARR from $500K to $700K is a capital efficiency crisis.\n\nBenchmark burn rates by stage (2024 US market): post-seed ($2–3M raised) — $80,000–$150,000/month is typical; post-Series A ($8–15M raised) — $300,000–$600,000/month; post-Series B ($20–50M raised) — $700,000–$2M/month. Burn multiples (net burn ÷ net new ARR) above 2× are considered capital inefficient; below 1× is excellent. During the 2023 VC downturn, investors shifted from growth-at-all-costs to prioritizing burn multiples under 1.5×.',
      example: 'A post-Series A startup with $8M in the bank and a $400,000/month net burn had 20 months of runway — enough time to reach the $5M ARR milestone needed for a Series B, with 6 months of buffer for a longer fundraising process.',
