      shortDef: 'The number of months a startup can operate before exhausting its cash reserves, calculated by dividing current cash by monthly net burn rate.',
      fullDef: 'Runway is the finite time horizon before a startup runs out of money. It is calculated as cash on hand divided by monthly net burn rate. A company with $3.6M in the bank burning $200,000/month net has 18 months of runway. Runway is the clock ticking against the milestones needed to raise the next round — and the single most important variable in startup capital planning.\n\nConventional wisdom says 18 months is the minimum safe runway post-raise, with 24 months as a comfortable target, given that fundraising itself typically takes 3–6 months and the last 6 months of runway are a psychological and operational emergency. Raising capital at 3 months of runway is raising from a position of desperation; term sheets at that stage often come with punitive terms.\n\nRunway decisions govern hiring pace: adding an engineer at $180,000/year costs $15,000/month in gross burn — equivalent to shortening runway by roughly 6 weeks on a $2M raise. Scenario analysis (best case: 25% burn reduction, worst case: 50% higher spend than planned) should be run before any major hiring decision. "Default alive" — the point at which projected revenue growth covers projected expenses before cash runs out — is the critical threshold that changes a startup\'s negotiating leverage with investors.',
