      shortDef: 'Customer Acquisition Cost — the fully loaded average cost to acquire one new paying customer, including all sales and marketing expenses divided by the number of new customers in that period.',
      fullDef: 'Customer Acquisition Cost (CAC) is calculated by dividing total sales and marketing expenses in a period (salaries, ad spend, events, tooling, agency fees — all costs dedicated to generating new customers) by the number of new customers acquired in that same period. A company spending $500,000/quarter on sales and marketing and acquiring 250 new customers has a CAC of $2,000.\n\nCAC should be segmented by channel (paid search vs. content vs. outbound sales vs. partner) to identify the most efficient acquisition pathways. Blended CAC (all channels combined) is reported to investors; channel-specific CAC drives internal growth experiments. CAC also varies by segment — enterprise deals may have a $50,000 CAC while SMB deals have a $500 CAC, and the ratio to LTV determines which segment is worth pursuing.\n\nThe CAC payback period — months of gross margin to recoup CAC — is a critical SaaS health metric. Best-in-class SaaS businesses target under 12 months CAC payback; 12–18 months is acceptable; above 24 months signals serious capital inefficiency. At $2,000 CAC and 70% gross margin with $100/month customer revenue ($70 gross margin/month), CAC payback is 28.6 months — too long for a capital-efficient business.',
      example: 'A B2B SaaS startup spent $180,000 on sales and marketing in Q3, acquired 90 new customers, yielding a blended CAC of $2,000; with an average ACV of $12,000 and 80% gross margin ($9,600 gross margin/customer), the CAC payback period was 2.5 months — exceptional capital efficiency.',
