      letter: 'L',
      shortDef: 'Customer Lifetime Value — the total gross margin contribution expected from a customer over their entire relationship with the business, used to evaluate whether CAC is justified.',
      fullDef: 'Customer Lifetime Value (LTV, sometimes CLV) is the present value of the total gross margin a business expects to receive from a single customer over the duration of the relationship. For SaaS businesses, LTV = (Average Monthly Revenue per Customer × Gross Margin %) ÷ Monthly Churn Rate. A SaaS business with $200/month average revenue, 70% gross margin, and 2% monthly churn has an LTV of ($200 × 0.70) ÷ 0.02 = $7,000.\n\nThe LTV:CAC ratio is the core health ratio for SaaS and subscription businesses. Industry benchmarks: LTV:CAC above 3× is healthy; above 5× suggests underinvestment in growth (could spend more on CAC to acquire customers profitably); below 2× indicates the business model is not working and unit economics need fundamental improvement before scaling.\n\nLTV is the most manipulable metric in startup reporting. Common mistakes: using revenue instead of gross margin (overstates LTV), using annual cohort data from early customers who haven\'t churned yet (survivorship bias), or assuming constant churn when churn typically increases over time. Best practice is to build LTV from actual cohort retention curves, discounting future cash flows at the company\'s cost of capital.',
      example: 'An e-commerce subscription box company calculated LTV as the gross margin from 24 months of average customer life ($45 gross margin/month × 24 months = $1,080 LTV) against a $320 CAC, yielding a 3.4× LTV:CAC ratio — sufficient to justify moderate paid acquisition scaling.',
