      slug: 'mrr-arr',
      letter: 'M',
      shortDef: 'Monthly Recurring Revenue and Annual Recurring Revenue — the predictable, contracted revenue components of a subscription business, excluding one-time fees and usage overages.',
      fullDef: 'MRR (Monthly Recurring Revenue) is the normalized monthly value of all recurring subscription contracts. ARR is MRR × 12. These metrics exclude non-recurring revenue (setup fees, professional services, hardware) and provide a clean measure of the predictable revenue base. For a SaaS company with 100 customers each paying $500/month, MRR = $50,000 and ARR = $600,000.\n\nMRR decomposition into components is essential for understanding growth health: New MRR (from new customers), Expansion MRR (upgrades and upsells to existing customers), Contraction MRR (downgrades), and Churned MRR (cancellations). Net New MRR = New + Expansion - Contraction - Churned. A company growing New MRR but with high Churned MRR has a "leaky bucket" problem that growth cannot solve permanently.\n\nNet Revenue Retention (NRR, also called Net Dollar Retention) measures expansion versus contraction and churn: NRR = (Beginning MRR + Expansion MRR - Contraction MRR - Churned MRR) ÷ Beginning MRR × 100%. Best-in-class SaaS businesses achieve 120%+ NRR, meaning that even with zero new customers, revenue from existing customers grows 20%+ annually through upsells — this is the compounding engine that makes SaaS highly valuable.',
      example: 'A project management SaaS entered January with $500K MRR, added $60K in New MRR, expanded $25K from upsells, and lost $15K to churn, ending at $570K MRR; their NRR was 114% — the existing customer base alone would grow ARR from $6M to $6.84M annually.',
