      term: 'Unit Economics',
      slug: 'unit-economics',
      letter: 'U',
      shortDef: 'The direct revenue and costs associated with a single unit of business (one customer, one transaction, one subscription), used to assess whether the fundamental business model is profitable at scale.',
      fullDef: 'Unit economics examines whether the fundamental transaction in a business generates more value than it costs. For a SaaS business, the "unit" is a customer: does the lifetime gross margin contribution (LTV) exceed the cost to acquire that customer (CAC)? For a marketplace, the unit is a transaction: does gross merchandise value (GMV) × take rate exceed the variable cost of facilitating the transaction? For DTC e-commerce, the unit is an order: does order revenue minus COGS minus fulfillment minus shipping minus return costs generate a positive contribution margin?\n\nPositive unit economics at the individual transaction level is necessary but not sufficient for a profitable business: fixed costs (engineering team, G&A, office) must also be covered. However, a business with negative unit economics cannot be fixed by growing faster — growth only increases losses. Identifying and fixing unit economic problems before scaling is why Y Combinator\'s primary advice is "make something people want" before growth.\n\nThe most common unit economics mistakes in early-stage companies: not including the full cost of customer service and support in CAC, using revenue instead of gross margin in LTV, ignoring the cost of acquired but non-converting trial users in CAC, and failing to segment unit economics by customer size (enterprise vs. SMB typically have dramatically different profiles).',
      example: 'A consumer subscription app had excellent-looking CAC ($12 via paid social) but poor unit economics because average subscription length was 2.1 months at $9.99/month and 60% gross margin, yielding LTV of $12.59 — barely above CAC and leaving no margin for operating costs.',
