      term: 'Break-Even Analysis',
      slug: 'break-even-analysis',
      letter: 'B',
      shortDef: 'A calculation determining the sales volume or revenue level at which total costs equal total revenue — the point where a business stops losing money and begins generating profit.',
      fullDef: 'Break-even analysis calculates the level of sales needed to cover all fixed and variable costs. The formula is: Break-even units = Fixed Costs ÷ (Price per Unit - Variable Cost per Unit). The denominator (Price - Variable Cost) is the contribution margin per unit — the amount each sale contributes toward covering fixed overhead after direct variable costs are paid.\n\nFor a SaaS business with $200,000/month in fixed costs (salaries, rent, SaaS tools), $100/month ACV per customer, and $20/month in variable costs (hosting, support), the contribution margin is $80/customer/month and break-even customer count is 200,000 ÷ 80 = 2,500 customers.\n\nBreak-even analysis is most useful for businesses with clear fixed cost structures and relatively stable unit economics. For early-stage startups with rapidly changing cost structures and growing teams, the more relevant concept is "default alive" — the point where projected revenue growth (based on current trajectory) exceeds projected expense growth, such that the company would become cash-flow positive before running out of money at current burn rate.',
      example: 'A restaurant calculated its break-even: $28,000/month in fixed costs (rent $12,000, labor $10,000, insurance/utilities $6,000) and a 35% contribution margin on food sales meant it needed $80,000/month in revenue ($28,000 ÷ 0.35) to break even — 267 covers per day at $30 average check.',
