      term: 'Go-to-Market Strategy',
      slug: 'go-to-market-strategy',
      letter: 'G',
      shortDef: 'The plan a company uses to bring a product to market — specifying target customers, distribution channels, pricing strategy, and positioning — to achieve commercial launch and growth objectives.',
      fullDef: 'A go-to-market (GTM) strategy is the operational blueprint for taking a product from development to commercial success. It answers: Who exactly is the target customer (ICP — Ideal Customer Profile)? What problem do we solve for them? How do they currently solve this problem and why is our solution better? What channels will we use to reach them (inbound content, outbound sales, product-led growth, partner channel, paid advertising)? At what price point? With what messaging?\n\nThe three primary GTM motions in B2B SaaS: (1) Sales-Led Growth (SLG) — dedicated sales team prospects and closes deals; effective for enterprise-ACV deals above $10,000/year where human relationships and procurement cycles justify the cost; (2) Product-Led Growth (PLG) — product itself drives acquisition, conversion, and expansion through free tiers, viral features, or land-and-expand; works for horizontal tools with broad audiences (Slack, Dropbox, Figma); (3) Marketing-Led Growth — content, SEO, and brand drive inbound leads that convert with minimal sales touch; effective for mid-market segments.\n\nGTM strategy failure is the most common reason for startup failure after product-market fit is achieved — roughly 40% of post-PMF startup failures per CB Insights. The most common GTM mistakes: targeting too broad an ICP (selling to anyone slows learning), choosing the wrong channel (enterprise product with a PLG-only motion), or under-investing in sales for products that require education.',
      example: 'A devtools startup with a $200/month prosumer product chose a PLG motion: free tier with unlimited users and 10 projects, upgrading to paid when teams needed unlimited projects; 78% of paid conversions came from teams that had used the free tier for 45+ days — validating the GTM assumption that developers need to experience value before approving budget.',
