      letter: 'P',
      shortDef: 'The state in which a product satisfies a strong market demand — evidenced by rapid organic growth, low voluntary churn, and users who would be very disappointed to lose the product.',
      fullDef: 'Product-market fit (PMF) is the degree to which a product satisfies a specific, sizable market need. Marc Andreessen coined the phrase in 2007; Sean Ellis quantified it: if 40%+ of users say they would be "very disappointed" if they could no longer use the product, it has PMF. Below 40% suggests the product needs to iterate on core value, target audience, or both.\n\nBehavioral signals of PMF include: organic word-of-mouth driving the majority of new users without paid acquisition, retention curves that flatten at a meaningful level (rather than continuing to decline toward zero), high NPS (Net Promoter Score of 40+ is the benchmark), and sales cycles that shorten as customer references become abundant. The feeling of PMF, per founders who have found it, is that the market is "pulling" the product out of the company rather than the company pushing.\n\nPMF is not binary and not permanent. A product may have PMF in a specific segment (SMBs in the US) but lack it in another (enterprises or international markets). It can also be lost when a competitive substitute enters the market or when customer needs evolve. Maintaining PMF at scale — as the ICP broadens and the product must serve more diverse needs — is one of the primary challenges in scaling from $5M to $50M ARR.',
