      shortDef: 'A market sizing framework: Total Addressable Market (all potential revenue), Serviceable Addressable Market (the segment you can reach), and Serviceable Obtainable Market (realistic near-term capture).',
      fullDef: 'TAM/SAM/SOM is the standard framework for defining market size in startup pitches and business plans. TAM (Total Addressable Market) is the total revenue opportunity if the product had 100% market share — typically estimated top-down from industry reports or bottom-up from number of potential customers × average spend. SAM (Serviceable Addressable Market) is the portion of TAM that the business can realistically serve given its current product, geography, and go-to-market approach. SOM (Serviceable Obtainable Market) is the realistic near-term capture of the SAM, usually a 3–5 year projection.\n\nInvestors and analysts scrutinize market sizing most carefully because VC math requires portfolio companies to reach $100M+ in revenue — which requires a SAM of at least $1B (10% market share is ambitious). A market sizing analysis that arrives at a $500M TAM immediately signals the opportunity is too small for venture capital, even if the business could be excellent.\n\nThe most credible market sizing combines top-down (industry reports: IBISWorld, Gartner, IDC) with bottom-up (company counts in target segment × estimated spend per company). Bottom-up analysis that directly ties to the ICP is far more credible to sophisticated investors than citing a large industry report and taking a small percentage.',
      example: 'A startup targeting legal document automation pitched: TAM = $25B (total US legal technology market), SAM = $3.2B (law firms with 10–200 attorneys in the US that use document management software), SOM = $80M over 5 years (2.5% SAM penetration at $8,000 ACV × 10,000 target firms); the bottom-up SOM calculation showing $8,000 ACV × 10,000 target firms made the projection credible.',
