      shortDef: 'Minimum Viable Product — the simplest version of a product that can be released to validate core assumptions with real users, generate learning, and avoid building features nobody wants.',
      fullDef: 'The MVP concept, popularized by Eric Ries in The Lean Startup (2011), is a learning tool, not a product strategy. The goal of an MVP is to test the riskiest business assumptions with the minimum investment of time and money. If the core assumption is "users will pay for X," the MVP is the simplest version of X that can generate a purchase decision — not a feature-complete product.\n\nMVPs take many forms: a landing page with an email signup to measure demand before building anything (Dropbox\'s explainer video pre-launch that generated 75,000 signups), a manual process disguised as software ("Wizard of Oz" testing), a concierge service where founders manually deliver what will eventually be automated (Airbnb\'s founders photographing apartments manually before building the platform), or a stripped-down functional product with one core use case.\n\nThe most common MVP mistake is making it too large — spending 6 months building an MVP that is really a V1 product. A true MVP should be buildable in 2–8 weeks for software products and testable with 5–50 users. The decision of what to cut from an MVP is the hardest and most important early product decision: cut everything that cannot directly falsify the core hypothesis.',
      example: 'A founder wanting to validate demand for AI contract review built an MVP in 3 days: a Typeform intake form, a Claude API prompt that reviewed contract PDFs, and a Google Docs output template — no custom software, no database. She tested 50 paying beta customers at $200/contract before writing a single line of proprietary code.',
