      shortDef: 'A structured change in strategy — target customer, product, revenue model, or distribution channel — made in response to evidence that the current approach is not achieving product-market fit.',
      fullDef: 'A pivot is a specific type of strategic change in which a startup keeps one foot in what is working (validated learning about customers or technology) while substantially changing another element of the business model. Eric Ries distinguishes pivots from abandonment: a pivot uses accumulated knowledge as a foundation, not a complete restart. Common pivot types: customer segment pivot (same product, different customer), value capture pivot (same product, different revenue model), channel pivot (same product, different distribution), and technology pivot (same customer problem, different technical approach).\n\nFamous pivots: Instagram pivoted from Burbn (a check-in app) to photo sharing, keeping the social and mobile elements; Slack pivoted from Glitch (an online game) to workplace messaging, reusing internal communication tools built for the game\'s development team; YouTube pivoted from a video dating site to general video sharing within 6 months of launch.\n\nThe decision to pivot requires distinguishing "persevere vs. pivot" — is the lack of traction due to poor execution (persevere, improve execution) or a fundamental flaw in the hypothesis (pivot, change the strategy)? Most failed startups pivot too late after burning through capital, while some pivot too early before giving an idea sufficient time to gain traction. Investors generally respect pivots that demonstrate learning; they are concerned about founders who pivot repeatedly without extracting and applying lessons.',
