      fullDef: 'Churn rate measures the rate at which a subscription business loses customers or revenue. Customer (logo) churn is the percentage of customers who cancel in a period: if 10 of 500 customers cancel in a month, monthly customer churn is 2%. Revenue churn (also called MRR churn) accounts for the fact that not all customers have equal value — a single $10,000/month enterprise customer canceling is more impactful than ten $1,000/month SMB cancellations.\n\nThe compounding effect of churn is why retention is the highest-leverage metric in SaaS: monthly churn of 2% implies that a cohort of 1,000 customers shrinks to 785 after 12 months, 617 after 24 months, and 485 after 36 months. Monthly churn of 5% leaves only 540 of that original cohort after 12 months. Best-in-class enterprise SaaS achieves monthly logo churn under 0.5% (annual retention above 94%); SMB SaaS benchmarks are 1–2% monthly churn.\n\nNegative churn (where expansion revenue from existing customers exceeds churned revenue) is the Holy Grail in SaaS. A company with -5% annual revenue churn means its existing customer base is growing even with zero new logo acquisition — every new customer added is pure incremental ARR growth on top of a growing base.',
