      fullDef: 'A trademark is any word, name, symbol, logo, slogan, sound, or combination thereof that identifies the source of goods or services and distinguishes them from competitors. Trademark rights arise from use in commerce (common law rights in the geographic area where the mark is used), but federal registration with the USPTO provides substantial additional benefits: nationwide priority, the right to use ® symbol, a legal presumption of ownership and validity, the ability to record the registration with US Customs to block infringing imports, and the right to sue in federal court for infringement.\n\nThe USPTO trademark application costs $250–$350 per international class of goods/services (TEAS Plus vs. TEAS Standard application). The process takes 8–18 months: an examining attorney reviews the application (typically within 3–6 months), may issue an Office Action requesting clarification or raising potential conflicts with existing marks, and if approved, publishes the mark for 30 days for opposition by third parties. Registered marks must be renewed between the 5th and 6th year after registration, then every 10 years.\n\nConducting a clearance search before adopting a new brand name is essential: the TESS database (free, USPTO) reveals registered marks, but common law marks not in the database can also create infringement exposure. A comprehensive clearance search through a trademark attorney or search firm costs $800–$1,500 but can prevent a costly rebrand down the road.',
