      fullDef: 'A Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA), also called a Confidentiality Agreement (CA), is a legally binding contract in which one or both parties agree not to disclose certain defined confidential information to third parties. Unilateral NDAs protect one party\'s information (e.g., a company sharing proprietary technology with a vendor); mutual NDAs protect both parties\' information (e.g., two companies exploring a partnership or M&A).\n\nNDAs are most useful in the early stages of a business relationship before trust is established, when sharing technical trade secrets, customer data, financial projections, or unreleased product plans. Key provisions to negotiate: definition of confidential information (broad vs. specific), exclusions (publicly available information, information already known to the recipient), permitted disclosure (required by law, regulatory bodies), term length (typically 2–5 years), and remedies (NDAs are enforced through injunctive relief and damages in court).\n\nStartup lore often overstates NDA utility with potential investors: reputable VCs and angels rarely sign NDAs before a first pitch meeting, as signing NDAs for every pitch creates legal risk given the volume of pitches and the likelihood of seeing similar ideas. The more productive approach for founders is to share enough to raise interest without revealing core trade secrets until a real due diligence relationship is established.',
      example: 'Before sharing its proprietary training dataset methodology with a potential acquirer during M&A due diligence, the startup required both companies\' CEOs to sign a mutual NDA with a 3-year term and specific definition of "Confidential Information" covering technical documentation, customer lists, and financial models.',
