      shortDef: 'A legal agreement transferring ownership of intellectual property created by founders or employees to the company, ensuring the business owns all relevant IP rather than the individuals who created it.',
      fullDef: 'An IP assignment agreement (often called a Proprietary Information and Inventions Assignment Agreement, or PIIA) is one of the most critical legal documents for any technology startup. Without it, IP created by founders and employees — code, algorithms, product designs, marketing materials — is legally owned by the individual creator, not the company. Investors and acquirers conduct IP ownership diligence and will block or significantly reduce valuations if IP ownership is unclear.\n\nFor founders, IP assignment should happen at company formation: each founder assigns all pre-existing relevant IP to the company (subject to a schedule of personal IP carve-outs they want to retain) and agrees that all future work-for-hire for the company is company property. For employees, an IP assignment agreement (typically bundled with the offer letter) ensures that inventions, code, and creative works produced within the scope of employment belong to the company.\n\nSome states limit IP assignment enforceability: California, Delaware, Illinois, Minnesota, North Carolina, and Washington have statutes that carve out inventions developed entirely on the employee\'s own time without company resources and outside the company\'s business. These protections for employees do not eliminate IP assignment for work within the employment scope but do require well-drafted agreements that comply with state-specific carve-out disclosures.',
      example: 'Before raising its seed round, a startup\'s attorney discovered that a co-founder had written the core algorithm 6 months before formation on a personal laptop and had never formally assigned it to the company; the assignment agreement was executed retroactively with consideration ($1.00 and the ongoing equity stake), clearing the IP chain of title for investors.',
