      fullDef: 'An employment agreement (also called an offer letter with attached employee agreements, or a full employment contract for senior executives) documents the terms of the employment relationship. For rank-and-file employees, many startups use a short offer letter plus a separately signed PIIA (IP assignment and confidentiality) and a stock option grant agreement. For executives and key employees, a more comprehensive employment agreement includes: compensation (base salary, bonus structure, equity), benefits, title and reporting structure, term and termination provisions (at-will employment with or without severance), non-compete/non-solicitation covenants, and IP assignment.\n\nAt-will employment (the default in 49 US states; Montana is the exception) allows either party to terminate the relationship at any time for any reason (except illegal discriminatory reasons). Most tech startup offer letters include at-will language. Exceptions: executives often negotiate severance provisions (6–12 months base salary and benefit continuation upon termination without cause), and co-founders often use vesting agreements rather than formal employment agreements for equity purposes.\n\nStart-up employment contracts frequently include: 90-day probationary periods, non-disclosure agreements (or separately signed NDAs), representations about not bringing prior employer IP to the new role, and acknowledgment that equity is subject to the full vesting schedule including applicable cliff periods.',
