      term: 'Loan Term',
      slug: 'loan-term',
      letter: 'L',
      shortDef: 'The length of an auto loan in months â€” typically 48â€“84 months â€” with longer terms reducing monthly payments but dramatically increasing total interest paid.',
      fullDef: 'Auto loan terms have stretched considerably over the past decade. In 2010, 60 months was the standard; today, 72-month loans are the most common, and 84-month (7-year) loans are offered widely. The allure is obvious: a 7-year loan drops the monthly payment on a $40,000 vehicle from $790/month (48-month at 6%) to $581/month (84-month at 6%) â€” a $209/month reduction. What\'s hidden: the 84-month loan costs $8,804 in total interest vs. $2,420 on the 48-month loan, a $6,384 difference.\n\nLong loan terms create negative equity risk because vehicle depreciation outpaces loan paydown. On an 84-month loan, you\'re paying mostly interest for the first 2â€“3 years â€” your principal balance barely moves. A car that loses 40% of its value in three years while your loan balance drops only 20% leaves you deeply underwater. Long-term loans also expose you to higher risk of repair costs before the vehicle is paid off.\n\nFinancial advisors typically recommend 60 months maximum for new vehicles, 48 months for used. If you can only afford the payment with an 84-month term, the vehicle is outside your budget. A useful rule: the monthly payment on a new car shouldn\'t exceed 15% of your monthly take-home pay, and the loan shouldn\'t extend beyond 60 months.',
      example: 'Two buyers finance the same $35,000 SUV at 7% APR. Buyer A chooses 48 months: $837/month, $5,176 total interest. Buyer B chooses 84 months: $531/month, $9,604 total interest. Buyer B\'s "cheaper" monthly payment costs $4,428 more over the life of the loan, and leaves them underwater for the first four years.',
      related: ['apr', 'negative-equity', 'interest-capitalization', 'balloon-payment'],
