      term: 'Credit Score Impact',
      slug: 'credit-score-impact',
      letter: 'C',
      shortDef: 'How auto loan applications and payment history affect your FICO score â€” hard inquiries cost 5â€“10 points short-term, while on-time payments build significant credit over a 60-month loan.',
      fullDef: 'Your credit score affects auto financing in two directions: it determines the rate you\'re offered (a 720 vs. 580 score can mean paying 8% more APR), and the auto loan itself affects your score going forward. Each credit application generates a "hard inquiry" reducing your score by 5â€“10 points temporarily. However, FICO\'s rate-shopping window allows multiple auto loan inquiries within 14â€“45 days (depending on scoring model) to count as a single inquiry â€” so shop multiple lenders simultaneously, not sequentially over several months.\n\nAn auto loan contributes to your score in several positive ways over time: it adds an installment account (good for credit mix), increases total account history, and every on-time payment adds to your payment history (35% of FICO score). A $30,000 auto loan paid perfectly over 60 months can increase a 680 score to 730+ by payoff. Conversely, a 30-day late payment drops most scores 60â€“110 points â€” potentially costing thousands in higher rates on future loans.\n\nBefore applying: check your credit report at annualcreditreport.com for errors (1 in 5 reports contain errors). Dispute inaccuracies before applying â€” fixing an erroneous 30-day late mark can increase your score 40â€“60 points and reduce your auto loan rate by 2â€“4%. Never let a dealer "shop" your loan to 20 lenders over 3 months â€” demand they batch applications within a 2-week window.',
      example: 'A buyer checks his credit at 695 before shopping. He finds an erroneous collection account, disputes it, and his score rises to 741 in 6 weeks. At 695, the best rate he was quoted was 8.9% APR. At 741, he qualifies for 5.7% APR. On a $36,000 60-month loan, that 3.2% difference saves $3,680 in interest.',
