      shortDef: 'A service contract extending coverage beyond the manufacturer\'s original warranty â€” sold by dealers, manufacturers, and third parties for $1,000â€“$4,000, with wide variation in value.',
      fullDef: 'Extended warranties (formally called Vehicle Service Contracts or VSCs) are contracts that pay for specific repairs after the factory warranty expires. They\'re one of the highest-margin products in the F&I office â€” dealers often earn $500â€“$1,500 profit per contract. Prices range from $1,200 for basic powertrain coverage on a 5-year-old economy car to $4,500 for comprehensive "bumper-to-bumper equivalent" coverage on a luxury vehicle. The F&I manager will often present these at the end of the deal when you\'re fatigued and emotionally committed â€” a calculated tactic.\n\nValue depends entirely on coverage terms, exclusions, deductibles, and the vehicle\'s reliability history. Most contracts exclude "wear items" (brakes, tires, filters), pre-existing conditions, and have fine-print exclusions for specific systems. A "comprehensive" contract on a BMW 3 Series might exclude the exact computerized systems most likely to fail. Read the sample contract, not the brochure. The best VSCs are manufacturer-backed (Toyota\'s ToyotaCare Plus, Ford\'s Extended Service Plan) â€” these have no third-party claim risk and are honored at any dealer.\n\nThird-party warranty companies have a concerning failure rate â€” the FTC estimates 30â€“40% of after-market extended warranty companies close within 5 years, leaving contract holders with void coverage and no recourse. If you want an extended warranty, buy manufacturer-direct, buy it from your credit union (they vet providers), or skip it entirely on vehicles with excellent long-term reliability records (Toyota, Honda, Mazda).',
      example: 'A dealer quotes a $3,200 extended warranty on a 2021 Ford Explorer. The buyer declines, invests the $3,200 in a high-yield savings account as a "car repair fund," and draws $1,400 in repairs over three years â€” coming out $1,800 ahead. On the other hand, his coworker with a 2021 Audi A6 paid $3,800 for a manufacturer extended warranty and had $7,200 in covered repairs in year four â€” a clear win.',
