      shortDef: 'The full 5-year cost of owning a vehicle including depreciation, financing, insurance, fuel, maintenance, and taxes â€” typically $35,000â€“$75,000 for most new vehicles.',
      fullDef: 'Total Cost of Ownership (TCO) is the complete financial picture of a vehicle over a defined period, usually 5 years. Edmunds\'s True Cost to Own model breaks this into five categories: depreciation (largest cost, 35â€“40% of TCO), financing (interest paid), insurance (15â€“20% of TCO), fuel (10â€“15%), and maintenance/repairs (10â€“15%). Government fees, taxes, and tires add the remainder. For a $35,000 mainstream SUV, five-year TCO typically runs $45,000â€“$55,000.\n\nTCO reveals why "cheap" vehicles aren\'t always cheap. A $28,000 Nissan Sentra might have a lower purchase price than a $33,000 Toyota Camry, but if the Camry has 30% better reliability ratings (less maintenance cost) and 15% better resale value (less depreciation), the Camry\'s 5-year TCO could actually be lower. Luxury vehicles are particularly misleading: a $55,000 BMW has dramatically higher insurance, maintenance (parts, dealer labor at $180/hour), and faster depreciation than a $55,000 Toyota Highlander.\n\nFuel costs have become a significant TCO differentiator as gas prices fluctuate. A full-size truck averaging 17 MPG vs. a crossover averaging 28 MPG represents a $2,000â€“$3,500 annual fuel cost difference at $3.50/gallon (15,000 miles/year). Over five years, that\'s $10,000â€“$17,500 in additional fuel cost that never appears on the window sticker but is very real to your household budget.',
      example: 'A buyer compares a $42,000 Ford F-150 and a $40,000 Toyota RAV4 Hybrid. F-150 five-year TCO: $68,400 (depreciation $20,100, fuel $13,500, insurance $9,800, finance $7,200, maintenance $4,900). RAV4 Hybrid TCO: $51,200. The "cheaper" truck costs $17,200 more over five years â€” equivalent to $287/month.',
