      shortDef: 'The manufacturer\'s recommended intervals for routine service (oil changes, filters, fluid flushes, inspections) â€” following it protects warranty coverage and prevents major failures.',
      fullDef: 'A preventive maintenance schedule is the factory-specified timeline for routine service tasks designed to keep a vehicle running reliably and protect warranty coverage. Modern vehicles using full synthetic oil have extended oil change intervals of 7,500â€“10,000 miles (some Toyota and BMW models stretch to 10,000â€“15,000 miles), replacing the old 3,000-mile conventional wisdom. Consult your owner\'s manual â€” the "severe duty" schedule (lots of short trips, dusty conditions, towing) calls for more frequent service; normal driving follows the standard schedule.\n\nKey maintenance milestones typically include: 30,000 miles (air filter, cabin filter, fuel filter inspection, tire rotation); 60,000 miles (spark plugs, brake fluid, coolant flush, possible timing belt on interference engines); 100,000 miles (spark plugs again on long-life plugs, transmission fluid, possible timing component inspection). Costs vary widely: a basic oil change runs $50â€“$120 at a quick-lube shop vs. $90â€“$200 at a dealership for synthetic. A full 60,000-mile service at a dealer runs $400â€“$900; an independent shop typically charges 30â€“50% less for identical work.\n\nDeferring maintenance creates compounding problems. Skipping transmission fluid changes ($150â€“$250) for 100,000 miles can lead to a $3,500 transmission rebuild. Ignoring coolant flushes ($100â€“$150) risks a $2,000 head gasket failure. The math strongly favors following the schedule â€” every $1 in preventive maintenance typically prevents $10â€“$20 in reactive repair costs.',
      example: 'A buyer skips the recommended 60,000-mile spark plug replacement ($280 at an independent shop) and coolant flush ($120) on his 2019 Kia Sorento. At 82,000 miles, misfires cause catalytic converter damage ($1,800) and the neglected cooling system overheats, warping a cylinder head ($2,400). Total deferred-maintenance cost: $4,200 vs. $400 in preventive service.',
