      shortDef: 'Replacement of brake pads and/or rotors â€” typically needed every 30,000â€“70,000 miles, costing $150â€“$600 per axle depending on vehicle and shop.',
      fullDef: 'A brake job (or brake service) typically involves replacing brake pads, and often rotors, on one or both axles. Pads wear over time from friction; rotors can warp, score, or thin below minimum thickness from heat and wear. Most vehicles need front pads every 30,000â€“50,000 miles and rear pads every 40,000â€“70,000 miles, depending on driving style (city stop-and-go wears brakes much faster than highway). Brake fluid should be tested annually and replaced every 2â€“3 years to maintain boiling point and prevent moisture contamination.\n\nCost varies dramatically by vehicle. A "budget" brake job on a Toyota Corolla at an independent shop (aftermarket pads + turned rotors) runs $180â€“$280 per axle. A performance brake job with OEM-spec pads and new rotors runs $300â€“$450 per axle. Luxury vehicles with larger rotors and proprietary pads (Porsche, BMW M) can cost $600â€“$900 per axle. Dealer pricing typically runs 40â€“60% higher than independent shops for identical work.\n\nWarning signs to act on immediately: squealing (wear indicator), grinding (metal on metal â€” rotor damage likely), pulsing/vibrating under braking (warped rotor), pulling to one side, soft or spongy pedal. Never ignore brake noises â€” driving another 3,000 miles on squealing pads can turn a $200 pad replacement into a $450 pad-plus-rotors job. If a shop quotes "four-wheel brake job" when front pads have 60% life remaining, get a second opinion.',
      example: 'A driver hears squealing from her 2020 Nissan Rogue at 52,000 miles. Quick-lube shop quotes $780 for "four-wheel brake service with new rotors." An independent brake specialist quotes $310 for front pads and rotors only (the rear still has 6mm of pad life). She saves $470 by getting a second opinion.',
