      shortDef: 'Scheduled replacement of transmission fluid to prevent wear and overheating â€” typically recommended every 30,000â€“60,000 miles, costing $100â€“$350, and skipping it risks a $2,000â€“$5,000 rebuild.',
      fullDef: 'Transmission service involves draining and replacing the transmission fluid, which lubricates and cools the complex gear and clutch mechanisms inside automatic, CVT, and dual-clutch transmissions. Over time, fluid breaks down from heat and develops abrasive metal particles from normal wear. Degraded fluid is the leading preventable cause of transmission failure. The service typically includes a fluid drain/fill or flush, filter replacement (on applicable models), and pan gasket replacement where accessible.\n\nService intervals vary by manufacturer and fluid type. Many automakers specify "lifetime fluid" on newer transmissions â€” a claim that means the fluid theoretically never needs changing. Most independent transmission specialists strongly disagree: they recommend changes every 30,000â€“60,000 miles regardless, especially for vehicles that tow, carry heavy loads, or operate in hot climates. Honda, Toyota, and Subaru have published CVT fluid change intervals of 25,000â€“60,000 miles. CVTs are particularly sensitive â€” degraded CVT fluid is responsible for a large percentage of CVT failures before 120,000 miles.\n\nA transmission fluid service costs $100â€“$250 at an independent shop; dealers charge $150â€“$350. A transmission rebuild or replacement costs $2,500â€“$5,500 for most vehicles, $4,000â€“$8,000+ for luxury vehicles or CVTs. The ROI on preventive service is extraordinarily high. When evaluating a used vehicle, ask for service records â€” if there\'s no evidence of transmission service after 60,000 miles, that\'s a meaningful risk factor.',
      example: 'A fleet manager with 40 company vehicles implements mandatory transmission fluid changes every 45,000 miles ($180/service). Over three years, zero transmission failures occur. His predecessor\'s records show 4 transmission replacements in the prior 3-year period at $3,400 average each â€” $13,600 in avoidable repairs vs. $7,200 in preventive services.',
