      letter: 'T',
      shortDef: 'Academic credits accepted by a new institution from previous coursework â€” typically transferable between regionally accredited schools, but acceptance rates and equivalencies vary widely.',
      fullDef: 'Transfer credits are credits from one institution accepted toward degree requirements at another. The transfer credit landscape is complex: regionally accredited colleges generally accept credits from other regionally accredited schools, but "accept" doesn\'t mean "apply to your major." A university might accept 90 transfer credits but only count 60 toward your specific degree program, requiring you to complete additional courses anyway. Community college transfers to four-year state universities in the same state generally have the clearest articulation agreements (formal credit transfer mappings).\n\nCredit acceptance rates depend on: course equivalency (a community college calculus course typically transfers as calculus; a communications class might transfer as an elective), minimum grade requirements (many schools require C or better), recency requirements (some programs won\'t accept credits more than 5â€“10 years old), and maximum transfer credit caps (most four-year schools cap transfer credits at 60â€“90 of the 120 required for graduation). STEM programs tend to be more restrictive; liberal arts programs more flexible.\n\nStrategic use of community college credits can save $20,000â€“$50,000. Completing the first two years at a community college at $100â€“$200/credit, then transferring to a state university for the final two years, is one of the highest-ROI higher education strategies available. Research articulation agreements between specific community colleges and target universities before enrolling â€” California\'s guaranteed transfer admission agreements (TAG) between CCs and UC system schools are a model example.',
      example: 'A student completes 60 credits at a community college ($4,800 in tuition at $80/credit). She transfers to a state university under a formal articulation agreement â€” all 60 credits apply directly to her degree requirements. She completes her final 60 credits at $280/credit ($16,800). Total degree cost: $21,600. Her classmate who started directly at the state university paid $33,600 for the same degree.',
