      shortDef: 'The per-credit-hour cost of college coursework â€” ranging from $80â€“$200 at community colleges to $400â€“$1,800 at private universities â€” the fundamental unit for comparing program costs.',
      fullDef: 'Tuition per credit hour is the basic unit of college cost, representing the charge for one credit of academic work (typically 1 hour of class per week for a semester). A 3-credit course costs 3x the per-credit rate; a 120-credit degree costs 120x the rate. For comparison: in-state public university tuition averages $350â€“$700/credit; out-of-state $800â€“$1,200/credit; private nonprofit $900â€“$1,800/credit; community college $80â€“$200/credit; online for-profit schools $250â€“$750/credit.\n\nOnline programs have democratized access to lower per-credit rates from reputable institutions. WGU (Western Governors University, regionally accredited) charges a flat per-term fee (~$3,750/6-month term) allowing students to complete as many credits as possible â€” aggressive learners complete a bachelor\'s in 2 years for under $15,000. Georgia Tech\'s online MSCS is $6,800 total for a master\'s degree vs. $43,000+ for the on-campus version. Arizona State Online has per-credit rates 30â€“50% below ASU\'s in-person tuition.\n\nWhen evaluating online programs, always calculate total degree cost (per-credit Ã— total credits required + fees + textbooks). Many schools advertise per-credit rates but bury mandatory fees that add $50â€“$200/credit. A program advertising "$350/credit" with $125 in mandatory per-credit fees is actually $475/credit. Compare apples-to-apples all-in costs.',
      example: 'Two regionally accredited online bachelor\'s programs offer identical degrees. School A: $750/credit Ã— 120 credits = $90,000 total. School B (WGU flat-rate): $3,750/term for unlimited credits â€” completing 20 credits/term = $375/effective credit, degree in 6 terms = $22,500 total. For a self-motivated student, WGU saves $67,500 for the same regional credential.',
