      shortDef: 'Free Application for Federal Student Aid â€” the required annual form that determines eligibility for federal grants, loans, and work-study for degree programs at accredited schools.',
      fullDef: 'The FAFSA (Free Application for Federal Student Aid) is the federal government\'s standard application for determining financial aid eligibility. It collects tax and financial information to calculate the Expected Family Contribution (EFC) â€” now called the Student Aid Index (SAI) â€” which schools use to determine aid packages. The FAFSA must be completed annually and submitted as early as possible after October 1 of the prior tax year (aid is awarded on a first-come, first-served basis for some programs).\n\nFAFSA determines eligibility for Pell Grants (free money, up to $7,395/year in 2024â€“25), federal subsidized and unsubsidized loans (2.75â€“5.5% fixed rates vs. 7â€“12% private loans), work-study programs, and most institutional grant aid. Only students enrolled at Title IV-eligible institutions (federally accredited) can receive FAFSA-based aid. Online students at regionally accredited universities qualify on the same basis as on-campus students.\n\nA key FAFSA mistake: failing to file because you think you earn "too much" to qualify. The income threshold for Pell Grants phases out around $60,000â€“$80,000 family income, but institutional grants, work-study, and access to low-rate federal loans apply at higher income levels. Graduate students are considered independent on the FAFSA (only their own income counts), making many graduate students eligible for aid they wouldn\'t qualify for as undergraduates. File every year, even if you received nothing the previous year â€” circumstances change.',
      example: 'A 28-year-old single parent returning to college online earns $31,000/year. She files the FAFSA and receives a $6,895 Pell Grant plus $5,500 in subsidized federal loans at 5.5% APR. Combined with employer tuition reimbursement of $5,250/year, her out-of-pocket for a $14,000/year online program is under $2,000. Without FAFSA, she would have taken private loans at 9.8% APR.',
