      shortDef: 'Federal need-based grant for low-income undergraduate students â€” up to $7,395/year in 2024â€“25 â€” that does not need to be repaid and is the foundation of federal student financial aid.',
      fullDef: 'The Pell Grant is the primary federal need-based grant program for undergraduate students, disbursed through FAFSA. Unlike loans, Pell Grants never require repayment â€” they\'re free money. The maximum award for the 2024â€“25 academic year is $7,395; actual award depends on the student\'s financial need (SAI), enrollment status (full-time vs. part-time), and cost of attendance at the school. Students at lower-cost institutions can receive the full Pell amount even if their tuition is less â€” remainder can cover living expenses, books, and transportation.\n\nPell Grant eligibility is limited to undergraduate students who have not yet earned a bachelor\'s degree and meet financial need thresholds. Students who previously defaulted on federal loans, have drug convictions from the time of enrollment, or exceed 12 semesters of Pell eligibility (6 full-time academic years) lose eligibility. Part-time students receive proportionally less: 3/4-time enrollment receives 75% of the full award.\n\nFor online students, Pell Grants work identically to in-person â€” the FAFSA process is the same, and aid is disbursed through the institution. One critical caveat: the school must be Title IV-eligible (nearly all regionally accredited schools qualify). Community colleges are disproportionately valuable Pell Grant destinations: a maximum $7,395 Pell Grant at a $4,000/year community college covers the entire tuition and generates a refund for living expenses. This makes community college effectively free for low-income students â€” a profoundly underused strategy.',
      example: 'A first-generation college student from a household earning $26,000/year receives a $7,200 Pell Grant annually. She attends an in-state online university charging $8,400/year in tuition. Her net tuition cost is $1,200/year ($4,800 for a 4-year degree), supplemented by $5,500/year in federal loans. Without the Pell Grant, she would have borrowed $33,600 vs. $22,000 â€” a $11,600 difference in debt.',
