      shortDef: 'A company benefit paying some or all of an employee\'s college tuition â€” typically $2,000â€“$5,250/year (IRS tax-free limit) â€” and one of the highest-ROI pathways to an online degree.',
      fullDef: 'Employer tuition reimbursement programs allow employees to pursue degrees or professional development with company financial support. The IRS allows up to $5,250/year in employer education assistance to be received tax-free (Section 127 of the tax code). Benefits above $5,250 are treated as taxable income. Approximately 56% of large US employers offer tuition assistance; typical maximum benefits range from $2,000â€“$5,250/year, though Amazon ($5,250/year, 95% upfront via Career Choice), Starbucks (100% tuition through ASU Online), Walmart ($1 degree through Guild Education with Live Better U), and others offer premium programs.\n\nMost programs require employees to maintain minimum GPA (2.0â€“3.0), remain employed during study, pursue degrees relevant to their role, and often work at the company 1â€“2 years after graduation (repayment clauses apply if you leave early). Reimbursement vs. pre-payment is an important distinction: many employers require you to pay tuition, then submit receipts for reimbursement â€” requiring cash flow management. Some newer programs (Amazon, Walmart) pay tuition directly upfront, eliminating the cash flow burden.\n\nCombining employer tuition reimbursement with FAFSA/Pell Grant is the highest-ROI degree pathway: a student receiving $5,250/year employer reimbursement + $4,000 Pell Grant covers $9,250/year in tuition on a program that might cost $10,000/year â€” leaving only $750/year out of pocket for a regionally accredited bachelor\'s degree.',
      example: 'A Target store manager uses Target\'s tuition benefit ($5,250/year) to complete a WGU online bachelor\'s in business administration ($7,500/year flat rate). Personal cost: $2,250/year, $9,000 total over 4 years. The degree qualifies her for a district manager role paying $28,000 more annually. Investment of $9,000 returns $28,000/year â€” 3x ROI in year one alone.',
