      slug: 'income-share-agreement',
      letter: 'I',
      shortDef: 'A financing arrangement where a school provides education in exchange for a percentage of future income â€” typically 8â€“17% of salary for 24â€“60 months after reaching a minimum income threshold.',
      fullDef: 'An Income Share Agreement (ISA) is a contract where a school or private investor covers education costs in exchange for a fixed percentage of the student\'s future income for a set period, contingent on earning above a minimum threshold. Key ISA terms include: income share percentage (typically 8â€“17%), payment term (24â€“60 months), payment cap (total maximum payment, often 1.3â€“2.5x the original amount), minimum income threshold (payments pause if income falls below $40,000â€“$50,000), and payment window (the total period including pauses).\n\nISAs are most prevalent in coding bootcamps and some alternative education providers. They can appear consumer-friendly (no risk if you don\'t get a job!) but require careful analysis. A $15,000 coding bootcamp with a 15% ISA for 36 months on a $70,000 salary costs $10,500 â€” seemingly better than $15,000. But if that same student earns $90,000, the ISA costs $13,500 at same term length; at $110,000, it costs the cap (often $22,500). Bootcamps benefit when graduates earn more; students benefit when outcomes are below projections.\n\nThe CFPB has scrutinized ISAs for compliance with consumer lending laws â€” some ISAs have been found to function as loans requiring Truth in Lending Act disclosures. Purdue\'s ISA program, one of the most prominent at a traditional university, suspended new ISA contracts in 2022. Before signing an ISA, calculate your total payment at multiple salary scenarios and compare to the equivalent loan with a fixed interest rate.',
      example: 'A student signs a $12,000 ISA at 12% for 30 months with a $45,000 income floor and a $24,000 cap. She earns $65,000 after bootcamp â€” payments are $650/month for 30 months ($19,500 total). Had she taken a $12,000 personal loan at 9% APR over 36 months, total cost would be $13,728. The ISA cost $5,772 more â€” and would have cost $24,000 (the cap) if she\'d earned $100,000+.',
