      shortDef: 'Return on investment of a college degree â€” calculated by comparing lifetime earnings premium minus total education cost â€” varies dramatically by field, school, and degree level.',
      fullDef: 'The ROI of a college degree measures the economic return relative to the full cost of obtaining it. Georgetown University\'s Center on Education and the Workforce tracks degree ROI by field and institution: the median bachelor\'s degree holder earns $1.2 million more over a lifetime than a high school graduate, but this average masks enormous variation. A computer science degree from a state university ($40,000 total cost, $85,000 starting salary) has extraordinarily high ROI; an art history degree from an $80,000/year private college ($320,000 total cost, $38,000 starting salary) has negative 20-year ROI.\n\nThe ROI calculation should include: total education cost (tuition + fees + books + living expenses + opportunity cost of wages not earned while studying), expected salary premium by field and degree level vs. alternatives, time to break even on investment, loan interest cost, and likelihood of employment in the target field. Tools like the College Scorecard (collegescorecard.ed.gov) now publish median 10-year-post-graduation earnings by school and program, providing the clearest public data available for ROI calculation.\n\nFor online degrees specifically, ROI is generally stronger than on-campus equivalents because: lower tuition at same accreditation level, ability to work while studying (reducing opportunity cost), and no relocation/housing premium. The caveat: certain programs (medicine, law, some research-oriented STEM) still benefit from on-campus networks and lab access that online can\'t replicate. For business, education, nursing, IT, and many liberal arts programs, the online ROI advantage is real.',
      example: 'A student considers a $90,000 private university nursing degree vs. an online nursing completion program at $28,000 (with an existing ADN). Both result in the same BSN credential, same salary ($72,000 starting), same career path. The $62,000 cost difference, invested at 6% for 30 years, grows to $356,000. The online path\'s ROI advantage: $62,000 saved + $356,000 in compounding = $418,000 lifetime difference.',
