      letter: 'P',
      shortDef: 'Identity verification and monitoring during online exams â€” conducted live (via webcam with human proctor) or via AI-based automated software â€” required by most accredited online programs for high-stakes assessments.',
      fullDef: 'Online proctoring ensures academic integrity for exams taken outside a physical testing center. Three main modalities exist: live remote proctoring (a human proctor monitors via webcam in real time), automated AI proctoring (software like ProctorU, Honorlock, Respondus Monitor, or ExamSoft flags suspicious behavior for later review), and in-person testing center proctoring (students travel to approved test centers). AI proctoring is now dominant due to cost ($15â€“$30 per exam vs. $50â€“$100 for live) and scalability.\n\nAI proctoring systems monitor: webcam feed for the student\'s face, browser activity (flagging tab-switching), eye movement, audio (detecting ambient voices), and keyboard patterns. Flags are reviewed by human reviewers post-exam. The technology is imperfect: false flags for students with disabilities, test anxiety behaviors, non-white faces (studies have documented racial bias in some AI proctoring systems), or simply having ADHD-related movement. Several universities have moved away from AI proctoring after documented equity concerns.\n\nFor students, proctoring requirements have practical implications: you need a reliable webcam, quiet private space, and a computer that meets system requirements. Some programs allow phone-based proctoring. Test-taking accommodations (extra time for documented disabilities) must be arranged through the school\'s disability services office â€” don\'t wait until exam week to request them. Most proctoring software requires a system compatibility check days before the exam.',
      example: 'A student preparing for a proctored CPA exam simulation discovers his older laptop fails the ProctorU system check (insufficient RAM for background monitoring). He borrows a newer laptop from his university\'s library for the exam day. Students who discover compatibility issues 10 minutes before an exam window opens face exam forfeiture â€” always run the system check 48 hours early.',
