      term: 'Cohort-Based Learning',
      slug: 'cohort-based-learning',
      letter: 'C',
      shortDef: 'An online learning format where a fixed group of students starts and progresses through a program together â€” offering stronger peer relationships and accountability than self-paced formats at the cost of schedule flexibility.',
      fullDef: 'Cohort-based learning structures students into groups (cohorts) that begin, advance through curriculum, and graduate together on a fixed schedule. This mirrors traditional on-campus education: students take the same courses simultaneously, collaborate on group projects, discuss cases together, and build professional networks with classmates who share career trajectories. MBA programs (Wharton Online, USC Marshall), nursing programs, and many professional master\'s degrees use cohort structures online.\n\nThe accountability effect of cohorts is real and measurable. MIT Sloan\'s research on online MBA programs found cohort-based formats have completion rates 15â€“25% higher than self-paced equivalents in similar demographic populations. When 25 peers are waiting on your contribution to a group project or when weekly live discussions have roll call, skipping becomes socially costly â€” a powerful nudge that self-paced formats lack entirely.\n\nTrade-offs are real: cohort programs have fixed start dates (often twice annually), can\'t be accelerated by motivated learners, and require consistent weekly schedule commitment. Self-paced programs suit people with unpredictable schedules or those who want to accelerate; cohort formats suit people who need external accountability structures and value peer networking. Premium online MBA programs with strong cohort structures (Questrom, Carey, Tepper) charge $45,000â€“$80,000 partly for the peer-network value.',
      example: 'A product manager enrolls in an online cohort MBA. His 45-person cohort includes two Google PMs, a fintech founder, and a hospital administrator â€” connections he actively uses for job referrals and advisory relationships post-graduation. He estimates his cohort\'s professional network has generated $40,000 in direct consulting work in the two years since graduation.',
