      letter: 'C',
      shortDef: 'The percentage of enrolled students who finish a program or course â€” typically 5â€“15% for free MOOCs, 50â€“70% for paid online degree programs, and a key indicator of program quality and student support.',
      fullDef: 'Completion rate measures how many students who begin a program ultimately finish it. Rates vary dramatically by format and price point: free MOOCs on Coursera and edX see 5â€“15% completion rates; paid certificate programs reach 40â€“60%; cohort-based online degree programs typically achieve 55â€“70%; traditional on-campus bachelor\'s programs average 60% six-year completion nationwide. The correlation with price and structure is strong â€” financial commitment and external accountability both drive completion.\n\nLow completion rates aren\'t always evidence of poor program quality â€” many MOOC enrollees audit out of curiosity with no intent to complete, inflating the denominator. But for degree programs, low completion is a warning sign: it often indicates poor student support infrastructure, unrealistic course loads, inaccessible faculty, or financial constraints forcing students out. The Department of Education publishes graduation rates for all Title IV schools at collegescorecard.ed.gov â€” check before enrolling.\n\nFor consumers evaluating programs, ask specifically about the program\'s completion rate (not institution-wide) and time-to-completion data. A 70% advertised completion rate that requires 7 years vs. 4 is very different from 70% in 4 years. Schools with strong completion support offer proactive advising, early-warning intervention systems (based on LMS engagement data), tutoring, mental health resources, and financial emergency grants â€” measurably better outcomes than programs where students are left to self-navigate.',
      example: 'A prospective student evaluates two online nursing programs. Program A touts a $15,000 cost but has a 42% completion rate (from College Scorecard). Program B costs $21,000 with a 74% completion rate. Factoring in that students who don\'t complete still accumulate debt but earn no credential, Program B\'s total expected cost (adjusting for non-completion probability) is lower per graduate.',
