      term: 'Password Manager',
      slug: 'password-manager',
      letter: 'P',
      shortDef: 'An application that generates, stores, and autofills strong unique passwords for every account, protected by one master password.',
      fullDef: 'A password manager solves the fundamental password problem: humans can\'t memorize a unique random 20-character password for every account, so they reuse passwordsâ€”creating credential-stuffing risk. A password manager generates cryptographically random passwords (e.g., "j7#Kp2@mQx9!sTv3") for each account, stores them in an encrypted vault, and autofills credentials in your browser and apps. You only remember one strong master password.\n\nVault encryption is typically AES-256 with PBKDF2, bcrypt, or Argon2 key derivationâ€”meaning even if the provider\'s servers are breached, the encrypted blob is computationally infeasible to crack without your master password. 1Password, Bitwarden, Dashlane, and KeePass are well-regarded options. Bitwarden is open-source and offers a free tier with unlimited passwords. 1Password\'s family plan ($5/month for 5 users) is popular for households. LastPass suffered a major breach in 2022 that exposed encrypted vaultsâ€”it\'s currently not recommended.\n\nBeyond password generation, modern password managers offer: breach alerts (notifying you when a stored password appears in a data breach), passkey storage (replacing passwords entirely on supported sites), secure note storage for SSH keys and license codes, and emergency access for family members. Pairing a password manager with MFA on every critical account is the single most impactful security step most individuals can take.',
      example: 'After a bank breach notification, a user discovers their password was the same one used on 12 other sites. They spend two hours with Bitwarden generating and saving unique passwords for all 12 accounts. Cost: $0 (free tier). Risk reduction: significantâ€”credential stuffing attacks on those accounts will now fail.',
