      term: 'Multi-Factor Authentication',
      slug: 'multi-factor-authentication',
      letter: 'M',
      shortDef: 'A security method requiring two or more forms of verification to access an accountâ€”typically something you know (password) plus something you have (phone) or something you are (fingerprint).',
      fullDef: 'Multi-factor authentication (MFA), often called two-factor authentication (2FA) when exactly two factors are used, dramatically raises the cost of account takeover. Even if an attacker has your password via phishing or a data breach, they still need your second factor. Microsoft\'s security research found that MFA blocks 99.9% of automated account-takeover attacks.\n\nMFA methods ranked by security (weakest to strongest): SMS one-time codes (vulnerable to SIM swapping and SS7 attacks), email OTPs (depends on email account security), authenticator apps like Google Authenticator or Authy (TOTP codes, much stronger), push notifications (convenient but vulnerable to MFA fatigue attacks), hardware security keys like YubiKey (phishing-resistant, FIDO2/WebAuthn standard, $25â€“$60 each), and passkeys (biometric-backed FIDO2 keys stored on your deviceâ€”the strongest and most user-friendly option).\n\nFor most people, switching from SMS to an authenticator app is a meaningful upgrade that takes five minutes per account. High-value accounts (email, banking, password manager) should ideally use a hardware key or passkey. Enable MFA on every account that offers itâ€”it\'s the most effective single security measure available to consumers.',
      example: 'A journalist\'s Twitter account credentials appear in a breach database sold on a dark web forum. An attacker attempts to log in using the stolen password. Because the journalist uses an authenticator app for MFA, the attacker is stoppedâ€”they have the password but not the 30-second rotating code. The attempt fails without the journalist ever knowing it happened.',
