      term: 'End-to-End Encryption',
      slug: 'end-to-end-encryption',
      letter: 'E',
      shortDef: 'Encryption where only the communicating users can read the messagesâ€”the service provider, ISP, or any third party cannot decrypt them in transit or at rest on servers.',
      fullDef: 'End-to-end encryption (E2EE) ensures that a message is encrypted on the sender\'s device and can only be decrypted by the recipient\'s device. The service provider\'s servers relay ciphertext they mathematically cannot read. This is distinct from transport encryption (TLS/HTTPS), where the provider encrypts traffic to their servers but can read content once it arrives. With E2EE, even a lawful government subpoena to the provider yields only useless ciphertext.\n\nApps with true E2EE by default: Signal (gold standard), WhatsApp (E2EE by default, owned by Meta), iMessage (between Apple devices), FaceTime. Apps with optional E2EE: Telegram (only in "Secret Chats"â€”regular chats are NOT E2EE). Standard SMS is not encrypted at all. Email services like ProtonMail and Tutanota offer E2EE between their users but not to external recipients unless PGP is used.\n\nE2EE protects against: interception by ISPs, Wi-Fi eavesdroppers, intelligence agencies, and the messaging company itself. It does not protect against a compromised endpoint device (malware on your phone can read messages before encryption), metadata (who you contacted and when is usually not encrypted), or someone with physical access to your unlocked device.',
