      term: 'Firewall',
      slug: 'firewall',
      letter: 'F',
      shortDef: 'A network security system that monitors and controls incoming and outgoing traffic based on predefined security rules, blocking unauthorized connections.',
      fullDef: 'A firewall acts as a gatekeeper between a trusted internal network and untrusted external networks (the internet). It inspects packetsâ€”the small units of data that travel across networksâ€”and allows or blocks them based on rules: source IP, destination IP, port number, and protocol. A basic stateful firewall tracks the state of connections and allows return traffic only for sessions initiated internally. Next-generation firewalls (NGFW) add application-layer inspection, intrusion detection, and threat intelligence feeds.\n\nFor home users, the router provided by your ISP includes a basic NAT-based firewall that blocks inbound unsolicited connections. Windows Defender Firewall and macOS Application Firewall provide host-based protection. For small businesses, dedicated firewall appliances from Fortinet, Palo Alto, or Ciscoâ€”ranging from $200 for a basic model to $10,000+ for enterprise gearâ€”add far more granular control. Cloud environments use security groups and network ACLs as their firewall layer.\n\nA firewall is necessary but not sufficient. It cannot stop phishing emails, malicious attachments that users open voluntarily, or attacks that travel over allowed ports (like web traffic on port 443). Layer your defenses: firewall for network perimeter, EDR for endpoint protection, email filtering for inbound threats, and user training for the human layer.',
