      term: 'DNS Filtering',
      slug: 'dns-filtering',
      letter: 'D',
      shortDef: 'A security control that blocks access to malicious, phishing, or prohibited domains at the DNS resolution level before any connection is established.',
      fullDef: 'DNS filtering intercepts DNS lookupsâ€”the process of translating a domain name like "evil-phish.com" into an IP addressâ€”and checks the requested domain against blocklists of known malicious, phishing, or inappropriate sites. If the domain is on a blocklist, the resolver returns a blocked response instead of the real IP, preventing the connection before any data is exchanged. Because DNS is used for virtually every internet connection, filtering at this layer is highly effective.\n\nPopular DNS filtering services: Cloudflare 1.1.1.1 for Families (free), Cisco Umbrella (business-grade, $2.20/user/month), NextDNS ($2/month personal), and OpenDNS (free tier). These services maintain threat intelligence feeds updated in near real-time. Cisco Umbrella blocks an average of 7 million malicious DNS queries per day across its customer base. Enterprise DNS filtering typically integrates with identity providers so policies can be applied per user or group.\n\nDNS filtering is one of the cheapest security controls availableâ€”often freeâ€”and protects all devices on a network, including IoT devices that can\'t run endpoint software. It doesn\'t replace other controls (a phishing site can move to a new domain within hours of being blocked) but adds a meaningful layer. Configure it at the router level for home networks so all connected devices benefit automatically.',
      example: 'An employee clicks a link in a phishing email while connected to the company network. Before the browser can load the spoofed login page, the company\'s DNS filter (Cisco Umbrella) recognizes the domainâ€”registered 12 hours ago, flagged in threat feedsâ€”and returns a block page. The credential theft attempt is stopped without any endpoint software being involved.',
