      term: 'Zero Trust',
      slug: 'zero-trust',
      letter: 'Z',
      shortDef: 'A security model that assumes no user or device is inherently trustworthy regardless of network location, requiring continuous verification before granting access to any resource.',
      fullDef: 'Traditional network security operated on a "castle and moat" model: strong perimeter defenses, but implicit trust for anything inside the network. Zero trust discards that assumption. Coined by Forrester analyst John Kindervag in 2010 and formalized in NIST SP 800-207, zero trust requires every access request to be verifiedâ€”regardless of whether it originates inside or outside the corporate networkâ€”before any resource is granted. The core principles: verify explicitly (authenticate and authorize every request using all available signals), use least-privilege access (give users and systems the minimum access needed), and assume breach (operate as if an attacker is already inside).\n\nIn practice, zero trust architectures implement: MFA for every login, device health checks before granting access (is this a managed device? does it have current patches?), micro-segmentation of networks so lateral movement is limited, conditional access policies that adjust based on risk signals (unusual location, new device), and continuous session monitoring. Major platforms implementing zero trust: Google BeyondCorp (which Google deploys internally), Microsoft Entra (formerly Azure AD), and Zscaler.\n\nThe business case is compelling: IBM\'s 2023 breach cost report found that organizations with mature zero trust deployments experienced breach costs averaging $1 million less than those without. Adoption has accelerated since the U.S. federal government mandated zero trust for all agencies in Executive Order 14028 (2021), with a compliance deadline of late 2024.',
      example: 'A company deploys a zero trust architecture. When a sales manager tries to access the CRM from an unrecognized device in a foreign country, the systemâ€”even though she provides correct credentials and passes MFAâ€”requires additional verification and limits access to read-only until IT confirms the session. An attacker using her stolen credentials from a data breach is blocked entirely.',
