      term: 'Data Breach',
      slug: 'data-breach',
      letter: 'D',
      shortDef: 'An incident where unauthorized parties access, steal, or expose sensitive, confidential, or protected data from an organization\'s systems.',
      fullDef: 'A data breach occurs when an attacker (or, in some cases, an insider) gains unauthorized access to systems containing sensitive information and extracts it. The data may include names, Social Security numbers, dates of birth, financial account numbers, medical records, login credentials, or intellectual property. Breaches occur through hacking (exploiting vulnerabilities), phishing and credential theft, malware, misconfigured cloud storage (S3 buckets set to public), and malicious insiders.\n\nThe financial impact is severe and multifaceted. IBM\'s 2023 Cost of a Data Breach Report puts the global average at $4.45 million per breach, rising to $10.93 million in healthcare. Costs include: forensic investigation, legal fees, regulatory fines (GDPR fines up to 4% of global revenue; HIPAA fines up to $1.9 million per category per year), notification costs (many states require notifying affected individuals within 30â€“72 hours), credit monitoring for victims, and reputational damage. Companies that experienced a breach saw an average 7.5% stock decline in the days following public disclosure.\n\nFor individuals: check HaveIBeenPwned.com to see if your email has been in known breaches. Change passwords for any breached accounts immediately, enable MFA, and monitor credit reports (free annually at AnnualCreditReport.com). Consider a credit freeze if financial data was exposed.',
