      term: 'GDPR',
      slug: 'gdpr',
      letter: 'G',
      shortDef: 'The General Data Protection Regulation is the EU\'s comprehensive data privacy law, giving individuals extensive rights over their personal data and imposing strict obligations on organizations that collect it.',
      fullDef: 'The General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), effective May 25, 2018, applies to any organization worldwide that processes personal data of EU residents. It grants individuals eight key rights: access (obtain a copy of all data held about you), rectification, erasure (the "right to be forgotten"), portability, restriction, objection, and rights related to automated decision-making. Organizations must have a lawful basis for processing dataâ€”typically consent, contract, or legitimate interestâ€”and must document that basis.\n\nEnforcement is vigorous. Fines can reach â‚¬20 million or 4% of global annual revenue, whichever is higher. Amazon received a â‚¬746 million fine in 2021 for advertising targeting practices. Meta has been fined over â‚¬1.2 billion cumulatively. WhatsApp was fined â‚¬225 million for transparency failures. Even smaller companies face six-figure fines: a Portuguese hospital was fined â‚¬400,000 for granting excessive database access to staff. Data breach notification must happen within 72 hours of discovery.\n\nFor US companies doing business with EU customers: appoint a Data Protection Officer if you process data at scale, conduct Data Protection Impact Assessments for high-risk processing, update your privacy policy to GDPR standards, implement data subject request workflows, and review all vendor contracts for GDPR-compliant data processing agreements.',
      example: 'A US-based SaaS company with 15,000 EU customers is fined â‚¬180,000 by the German DPA after an audit reveals they were sending EU customer data to a third-party analytics vendor without a Data Processing Agreement and without informing users in their privacy policy.',
