      shortDef: 'The California Consumer Privacy Act gives California residents rights to know, delete, and opt out of the sale of their personal information, with civil penalties for violations.',
      fullDef: 'The California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), effective January 1, 2020, and strengthened by the California Privacy Rights Act (CPRA) in 2023, grants California residents the right to: know what personal information businesses collect about them and why, request deletion of that information, opt out of the sale or sharing of their personal information, correct inaccurate information, and limit use of sensitive personal information (precise geolocation, race, religion, health data).\n\nCCPA applies to for-profit businesses that meet any one of three thresholds: annual gross revenue above $25 million, buying/selling/sharing personal information of 100,000+ consumers or households annually, or deriving 50%+ of annual revenue from selling personal information. Enforcement is by the California Privacy Protection Agency and the California AG. Civil penalties run $2,500 per unintentional violation and $7,500 per intentional violationâ€”in a class action scenario, those numbers add up quickly.\n\nFor businesses: implement a "Do Not Sell or Share My Personal Information" link (can be the Global Privacy Control browser signal), build a consumer request portal with 45-day response SLA, update your privacy policy, audit your data flows and vendor agreements, and train customer-facing staff. CCPA is the most consequential US privacy law to date and has inspired similar legislation in Virginia, Colorado, Connecticut, and over a dozen other states.',
      example: 'A California resident submits a CCPA data access request to a data broker. Under CCPA, the broker must respond within 45 days. The response reveals the broker holds 47 data points on the residentâ€”home value estimate, estimated income, purchase history inferences, and political affiliation. The resident then submits a deletion request for all of it.',
