      term: 'PII',
      slug: 'pii',
      letter: 'P',
      shortDef: 'Personally Identifiable Information is any data that can be used to identify a specific individual, either alone or combined with other information.',
      fullDef: 'PII (Personally Identifiable Information) encompasses two categories. Directly identifying PII needs no additional context: full name, Social Security number, driver\'s license number, passport number, financial account numbers, biometric data. Quasi-identifying or indirect PII can identify someone when combined: date of birth, ZIP code, job title, IP address, device ID, or location data. A 1997 study by Latanya Sweeney found that 87% of Americans could be uniquely identified using only ZIP code, birth date, and sex.\n\nPII is the primary target of data breaches, identity theft, and unauthorized surveillance because it has direct monetary value: a full identity profile (name, SSN, DOB, address, credit card) sells for $20â€“$200 on dark web markets. Healthcare PII (full medical record) commands $250â€“$1,000 because it enables insurance fraud and prescription drug scams. Organizations holding PII face significant legal exposure under GDPR, HIPAA, CCPA, and state breach notification laws.\n\nConsumers should: minimize PII shared with apps and services (do you really need to give a loyalty card app your birthdate?), use aliases where possible, review app permissions regularly (location access is PII), and freeze credit to reduce the damage if SSN is compromised. Organizations should apply data minimization principlesâ€”collect only the PII actually needed, store it encrypted, and delete it when no longer required.',
      example: 'A health app requires users to enter name, date of birth, weight, and medical conditions during signup. This is sensitive PII. When the startup is acquired and sold its user database to a third party, users receive no notificationâ€”triggering a CCPA complaint and an investigation by the California AG.',
