      shortDef: 'A service that continuously scans dark web forums, marketplaces, and paste sites for your personal information and credentials and alerts you when they appear.',
      fullDef: 'The dark webâ€”sites reachable only via Tor or specialized networksâ€”hosts markets and forums where stolen data is bought and sold: credential dumps, full identity packages, credit card numbers, medical records, and corporate intellectual property. Dark web monitoring services use automated crawlers and human intelligence to scan these platforms, then compare findings against your registered email addresses, SSNs, credit card numbers, and phone numbers, alerting you within hours or days of a discovery.\n\nServices range from free (HaveIBeenPwned.com for email addresses; Google\'s "Results About You" for personal info; credit card issuers\' built-in monitoring) to paid. Experian IdentityWorks at $25/month monitors SSN, bank accounts, credit cards, phone numbers, and sends real-time alerts. Identity Guard and Aura ($12â€“$17/month) offer broader monitoring with insurance. Some password managers (1Password, Bitwarden) include free breach notifications tied to stored accounts.\n\nWhen a dark web alert fires, the action priority is: immediately change the exposed password (or reset the account), enable MFA if not already active, check account activity for unauthorized access, and place a fraud alert or credit freeze if financial or SSN data was exposed. Monitoring is reactiveâ€”it tells you after exposureâ€”so it\'s most valuable when paired with proactive controls like strong unique passwords and MFA.',
