      term: 'Right to Be Forgotten',
      slug: 'right-to-be-forgotten',
      letter: 'R',
      shortDef: 'A legal right, established under GDPR, allowing individuals to request deletion of their personal data from an organization\'s systems and, in some cases, from search engine results.',
      fullDef: 'The right to erasureâ€”commonly called the right to be forgottenâ€”is codified in Article 17 of GDPR. It entitles EU residents to request that an organization delete all personal data it holds about them when: the data is no longer necessary for the original purpose, the individual withdraws consent, the individual objects to processing for legitimate interests, or the data was unlawfully processed. Organizations have one month to comply; they can extend to three months for complex requests.\n\nFor search engines, the right to be forgotten operates differently. Following the landmark 2014 EU Court of Justice ruling in Google Spain v. AEPD, individuals can request that Google (and other engines) delist specific URLs from results for searches on their nameâ€”even if the underlying page remains public. Google has received over 5.4 million delisting requests since 2014 and has removed approximately 47% of requested URLs. Grounds must be legitimate: outdated, irrelevant, or disproportionately harmful information. Public figures face a higher bar than private individuals.\n\nIn the US, no federal right to erasure exists for general data. CCPA provides California residents a deletion right against covered businesses. COPPA requires deletion of children\'s data on request. For search engine delisting, US options are limited to contacting websites directly, filing defamation claims in court, or using reputation management services ($1,000â€“$10,000/month) that attempt to suppress unwanted results through SEO rather than legal removal.',
      example: 'A European professional had a minor criminal charge from 2009 that was dropped appearing prominently in Google search results for her name, affecting job applications. She filed a GDPR Article 17 erasure request with Google, which evaluated the request and removed the links from search results for her name within six weeks.',
