      fullDef: 'The Licensed Professional Counselor (LPC) credentialâ€”called LPCC (Licensed Professional Clinical Counselor) in California and some other statesâ€”is the counseling profession\'s primary independent practice license. The training path: master\'s degree in counseling or clinical mental health counseling (60 semester hours, CACREP-accredited programs preferred), 2â€“3 years of supervised post-degree experience (typically 3,000 hours), and a licensing exam (the NCE or NCMHCE). LPCs are regulated by state licensure boards, often titled boards of counseling.\n\nLPCs are trained in the wellness and developmental model of mental healthâ€”viewing psychological distress as a normal response to life challenges rather than diseaseâ€”which shapes a collaborative, strengths-based approach. They are highly trained in career counseling, multicultural counseling, and school-based mental health (the Licensed Professional School Counselor is a related specialty). In private practice and community mental health settings, LPCs provide the full range of evidence-based therapies including CBT, DBT, EMDR, and ACT.\n\nInsurance parity is important to understand: LPCs are recognized providers by most major commercial insurers, Medicare (since 2024â€”this was a significant policy change), and Medicaid in most states. Average private practice rate: $120â€“$220/session. The LPC and LCSW credentials are functionally equivalent for most clients seeking outpatient psychotherapy; the choice between them should be based on the specific clinician\'s training, experience, and approach rather than the credential letters.',
