      fullDef: 'The Licensed Marriage and Family Therapist (LMFT) credential trains clinicians in systemic and relational approachesâ€”viewing individuals\' problems within the context of their family system, couple relationship, or other relational context. Training: master\'s degree in Marriage and Family Therapy (60 credit hours, COAMFTE-accredited programs), 2+ years of supervised clinical experience (500 hours of direct client contact with supervision), and a licensing exam (the MFT national exam). LMFTs are licensed by state boards of behavioral sciences or similar agencies.\n\nSystemic therapy, the core framework of MFT training, holds that symptoms in an individual often serve a function within the larger family or relational system. Key models include Emotionally Focused Therapy (EFT) for couples (the most evidence-based couples therapy, with 70â€“75% of couples achieving full recovery per meta-analysis), Structural Family Therapy, and Narrative Therapy. LMFTs can work with individuals, couples, and families; approximately 35% of their caseload involves couples therapy and 30% involves family therapy.\n\nFor couples therapy specifically, LMFTs with Certified Gottman Therapist or EFT Supervisor certification are considered the gold standard. Average couples therapy session with an LMFT: $150â€“$300; insurance coverage for couples therapy varies significantlyâ€”many plans cover it only when one partner has a documented mental health diagnosis, as couples therapy itself is not a DSM diagnosis. Always verify coverage before assuming insurance will apply.',
