      shortDef: 'The Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, Fifth Edition, is the American Psychiatric Association\'s standard classification system for mental health disorders used by clinicians and insurers.',
      fullDef: 'The DSM-5 (updated to DSM-5-TR in 2022 with text revisions) is the primary diagnostic reference used by mental health clinicians in the United States to classify and define mental health conditions. It describes over 300 mental disorders with diagnostic criteriaâ€”specific symptoms, duration requirements, and functional impairment thresholds that must be met for a diagnosis. Diagnoses are coded with ICD-10-CM codes (used for insurance billing), which map to the DSM categories.\n\nThe DSM serves several critical functions: it creates a shared language between clinicians, enables insurance billing (a DSM diagnosis is required for most insurance-covered mental health treatment), guides treatment decisions, and structures research. However, its limitations are widely discussed: psychiatric diagnoses are based on symptom clusters rather than biological tests, comorbidity is the rule rather than the exception (most people with depression also have anxiety; most with PTSD have depression), and dimensional approaches to mental health are arguably more accurate than discrete categories.\n\nFor patients, the practical implications: a DSM diagnosis is required for your insurer to cover mental health treatment. If your therapist isn\'t assigning a diagnosis, they\'re likely billing under a "V-code" (a problem code like "relationship distress") which many insurers don\'t cover. Ask your clinician what diagnosis is on your insurance claims. Common billable diagnoses include F32 (major depressive disorder), F41 (anxiety disorders), F43 (stress-related disorders including PTSD), and F90 (ADHD).',
