      shortDef: 'A category of mental health conditions characterized by excessive, persistent fear or worry that significantly impairs daily functioning, including GAD, panic disorder, social anxiety, and specific phobias.',
      fullDef: 'Anxiety disorders are the most prevalent mental health condition in the US, affecting 31.1% of adults at some point in their lives per the National Comorbidity Survey Replication. The DSM-5 lists distinct anxiety disorders: Generalized Anxiety Disorder (GADâ€”excessive worry about multiple domains for 6+ months), Panic Disorder (recurrent unexpected panic attacks with anticipatory anxiety), Social Anxiety Disorder (intense fear of social situations with scrutiny), Specific Phobia (marked fear of a specific stimulus), Agoraphobia, and Separation Anxiety Disorder. OCD and PTSD are related but classified separately.\n\nAnxiety disorders cause real functional impairment: missed work, relationship avoidance, emergency department visits for panic attacks (average cost: $1,500â€“$3,000 for cardiac workup that rules out heart problems), and untreated substance use as self-medication. The economic burden of anxiety disorders in the US exceeds $46 billion annually in lost productivity and healthcare costs.\n\nFirst-line treatments are CBT (particularly exposure-based CBT) and SSRIs/SNRIs. Response rates to CBT for specific phobias reach 80â€“90% in 8â€“15 sessions. For GAD, combination treatment (CBT + medication) outperforms either alone. The biggest barrier to treatment is time: the median delay between anxiety symptom onset and first treatment is 11 years per NAMI data. Starting treatment early dramatically improves outcomes.',
      example: 'A 26-year-old with social anxiety disorder avoids job interviews, networking events, and speaking in meetingsâ€”limiting her to entry-level positions despite strong qualifications. After 16 sessions of exposure-based CBT ($140/session, 12 in-network), she completes three interviews and accepts a role with $18,000 higher salary than her previous job.',
