      fullDef: 'Major Depressive Disorder (MDD) affects approximately 21 million US adults annuallyâ€”8.3% of the adult populationâ€”making it the leading cause of disability in the US for adults ages 15â€“44. Diagnostic criteria require 5 or more of 9 symptoms for at least two weeks: depressed mood most of the day, loss of interest or pleasure (anhedonia), significant weight change, sleep disturbance (insomnia or hypersomnia), psychomotor agitation or slowing, fatigue, feelings of worthlessness or excessive guilt, difficulty concentrating, and recurrent thoughts of death or suicidal ideation. At least one symptom must be depressed mood or anhedonia.\n\nTreatment response: 40â€“60% of patients respond to the first antidepressant tried; switching or augmenting brings 60â€“70% of patients to response. Full remissionâ€”not just responseâ€”is the treatment goal and achieved in roughly 30â€“40% of patients with first-line medication. The STAR*D trial, the largest antidepressant study ever conducted (4,041 patients), found that after four treatment steps, only 67% of patients achieved remission. This underscores the importance of continuing to adjust treatment rather than accepting partial response.\n\nCost without treatment is substantial: depression costs the US $210 billion annually in lost productivity, healthcare utilization, and direct costs. Workers with untreated depression miss an average of 27 additional days per year. Effective treatmentâ€”even accounting for therapy and medication costs of $200â€“$500/monthâ€”produces strong return on investment through reduced absenteeism and healthcare use.',
