      fullDef: 'PTSD affects approximately 3.5% of US adults annuallyâ€”about 9 million peopleâ€”with lifetime prevalence around 8.7%. It develops after direct or witnessed trauma: combat, sexual assault, accidents, natural disasters, childhood abuse, or sudden loss. Not everyone exposed to trauma develops PTSD; risk factors include prior trauma history, dissociation during the event, lack of social support, and genetic factors. Women develop PTSD at roughly twice the rate of men after equivalent trauma exposure.\n\nDSM-5 requires symptoms across four clusters for 1+ month with significant impairment: intrusion (flashbacks, nightmares, intrusive memories), avoidance (avoiding internal reminders or external triggers), negative alterations in cognition and mood (persistent distorted blame, emotional numbing, persistent negative emotions), and marked alterations in arousal (hypervigilance, exaggerated startle, sleep disturbance). PTSD in veterans: 11â€“20% of Iraq/Afghanistan veterans have PTSD in a given year; approximately 500,000 veterans receive PTSD disability compensation annually.\n\nGold-standard treatments: Prolonged Exposure (PE) and Cognitive Processing Therapy (CPT) are VA/DoD first-line recommendations, each with 70â€“80% response rates in 8â€“15 sessions. EMDR is equally effective. Medication (SSRIs sertraline and paroxetine are FDA-approved for PTSD) provides moderate benefit. VA provides PE and CPT at no cost to veterans; civilian access depends on finding trained therapists, which remains a significant barrier.',
      example: 'A sexual assault survivor scores a PCL-5 of 58 (severe PTSD) before starting CPT. Over 12 weekly 60-minute sessions ($175/session, 8 covered by insurance after $1,200 deductible), her therapist helps her identify and challenge "stuck points"â€”beliefs like "it was my fault" and "I am permanently damaged." Post-treatment PCL-5: 21, below the clinical threshold.',
