      shortDef: 'Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder involves unwanted intrusive thoughts (obsessions) and repetitive behaviors or mental acts (compulsions) performed to reduce distress, often consuming 1+ hours daily.',
      fullDef: 'OCD affects approximately 2.3% of the US populationâ€”about 7.5 million adultsâ€”and is classified by the World Health Organization as one of the top 10 most disabling illnesses due to the degree of functional impairment it causes. The cycle: an intrusive thought triggers intense anxiety, a compulsion temporarily reduces that anxiety, which reinforces the belief that the compulsion is necessary and makes the next intrusive thought more distressing. Compulsions include visible behaviors (checking locks 40 times, hand washing until bleeding) and mental acts (reviewing, neutralizing, praying).\n\nOCD is frequently misdiagnosed and undertreatedâ€”average time from symptom onset to correct diagnosis is 14â€“17 years per the International OCD Foundation. Many therapists without OCD specialty training inadvertently worsen symptoms by providing excessive reassurance or supporting avoidance. The correct treatment is Exposure and Response Prevention (ERP)â€”a specialized form of CBT in which clients deliberately confront feared thoughts/situations without performing compulsions. ERP produces clinically significant improvement in 60â€“80% of patients, typically in 12â€“20 sessions. Finding a therapist trained in ERP is critical: the IOCDF therapist directory (iocdf.org) lists ERP-trained providers nationwide.\n\nMedication: SSRIs are first-line (higher doses than used for depressionâ€”typically 200mg sertraline or 300mg fluvoxamine); clomipramine (an older TCA) is highly effective but with more side effects. 40â€“60% of patients respond to medication alone; combination with ERP produces the best outcomes. For treatment-resistant OCD, deep brain stimulation (DBS) has received FDA breakthrough device designation.',
      example: 'A 30-year-old spends 3â€“4 hours/day checking that the stove is off, doors are locked, and the car is in park. His OCD causes him to be late to work and has led to two disciplinary actions. After 16 sessions of ERP with an IOCDF-listed therapist ($200/session, 8 covered in-network), checking behaviors drop to 20 minutes/day. He practices deliberately leaving the stove unverifiedâ€”initially causing severe anxiety that extinguishes over repeated trials.',
