      fullDef: 'ADHD affects approximately 8.7% of US children and 4.4% of adults, making it one of the most common neurodevelopmental conditions. The three presentations under DSM-5: predominantly inattentive (difficulty sustaining attention, losing things, forgetting, easily distracted), predominantly hyperactive-impulsive (fidgeting, leaving seat, talking excessively, difficulty waiting), and combined presentation. Adult ADHD is frequently underdiagnosed, particularly in womenâ€”who more often present with inattentive symptoms that are subtler than the hyperactive behaviors that lead to childhood diagnosis in boys.\n\nDiagnosis requires a comprehensive evaluation (psychiatric interview, behavioral rating scales like the Conners or BAARS-IV, cognitive testing in some cases, and gathering history from multiple informants). A thorough psychiatric evaluation costs $300â€“$800 cash pay; some primary care physicians diagnose and prescribe for straightforward cases. Stimulant medications (methylphenidate, amphetamine salts) are highly effective with 70â€“80% response rates; non-stimulants (atomoxetine, guanfacine, bupropion) are used when stimulants are contraindicated.\n\nThe economic impact of untreated ADHD is significant: adults with untreated ADHD earn an estimated $10,000â€“$30,000 less annually than neurotypical peers, have higher rates of divorce, accidents, job changes, and substance use. ADHD coaching ($150â€“$300/month) and CBT for ADHD (targeting executive function deficits) are valuable adjuncts to medication. Workplace accommodations (extended deadlines, quiet work environments) are legally available under the ADA.',
