      fullDef: 'Bipolar disorder affects approximately 2.8% of US adults (about 7 million people) and is divided into Bipolar I (at least one manic episode lasting 7+ days or requiring hospitalization, with or without depressive episodes), Bipolar II (hypomanic episodes that are less severe than full mania, plus major depressive episodesâ€”often underdiagnosed as recurrent depression), and Cyclothymic Disorder (chronic mild cycling). Mania involves elevated or irritable mood, decreased need for sleep (3 hours feeling rested), grandiosity, racing thoughts, increased goal-directed activity, and risky behavior; hypomania has the same features but is less severe and doesn\'t cause marked impairment.\n\nBipolar I disorder has a lifetime risk of suicide that is 20â€“30 times higher than the general populationâ€”15% of untreated or undertreated patients die by suicide. Correct diagnosis is challenging: the average person with bipolar disorder sees 3.5 clinicians and waits 10 years before receiving the correct diagnosis, often because depressive episodes are the presenting complaint. Treatment with antidepressants alone (without mood stabilizers) in bipolar disorder can trigger mania or rapid cyclingâ€”making accurate diagnosis essential.\n\nFirst-line mood stabilizers: lithium (most evidence-based, reduces suicide risk by 80â€“85%, requires blood monitoring every 6 months, cost $20â€“$40/month generic), valproate, and lamotrigine. Atypical antipsychotics (quetiapine, aripiprazole, olanzapine) are used for acute episodes and maintenance. Psychotherapyâ€”particularly psychoeducation, IPSRT (Interpersonal and Social Rhythm Therapy), and CBTâ€”significantly reduces relapse rates when combined with medication.',
