      fullDef: 'Therapy pricing in the US is highly variable. At the low end: EAP (Employee Assistance Program) sessions are free, typically covering 6â€“12 sessions per year. Community mental health centers charge $0â€“$50 on sliding scale for qualifying patients. Federally Qualified Health Centers (FQHCs) provide therapy on a sliding scale starting at $20â€“$40/session. Graduate training clinics (supervised masters and doctoral students) charge $30â€“$80/session.\n\nPrivate practice rates vary by geography, credential, and specialty: rural areas average $80â€“$120/session (master\'s-level); suburban areas $120â€“$200; major cities (NYC, LA, SF, Boston) $200â€“$350 for experienced licensed clinicians. Specialties with premiums: EMDR ($180â€“$300), DBT ($200â€“$350 for individual plus group costs), eating disorder specialists, and neuropsychological testing ($2,000â€“$5,000 for a full battery). A 2022 Therapy Den survey found the median therapy fee was $150/session nationally.\n\nWith insurance: in-network therapy copays typically run $20â€“$60 after deductible for the standard 45- or 53-minute CPT codes (90834/90837). Out-of-network reimbursementâ€”if your plan has itâ€”covers 50â€“80% of the "allowed amount" after deductible. On average, patients pay 40â€“60% less per session in-network versus out-of-pocket cash pay. Platforms like Open Path Collective offer reduced-fee sessions with licensed clinicians ($30â€“$80/session) for those without adequate coverage.',
