      fullDef: 'Sliding scale fees allow therapists in private practice, community health centers, and training clinics to serve clients whose income doesn\'t support full rates while still sustaining their practice. A typical private practice therapist might offer a standard rate of $180/session but set their sliding scale range at $80â€“$180, with the fee determined by a brief income and household size assessment. Training clinics at universities often have floors of $30â€“$40 regardless of income. Some therapists use a community accountability model (asking clients to self-select their fee from a range).\n\nFinding sliding scale therapists: Psychology Today\'s therapist directory allows filtering by sliding scale. Open Path Collective is a network of licensed clinicians who offer sessions at $30â€“$80 specifically to low- and moderate-income clients (annual membership fee $65). The National Alliance on Mental Illness (NAMI) helpline (1-800-950-6264) can direct callers to local free or low-cost resources. Federally Qualified Health Centers are required by law to provide services on a sliding scale based on income.\n\nReality check: many therapists advertise sliding scale but have limited low-fee slots. For the highest-need clients, community mental health centersâ€”which receive federal and state funding specifically to serve uninsured and low-income individualsâ€”are often the best option, offering $0â€“$30 fees. Medicaid covers outpatient mental health therapy at most agencies; in 2023, all 50 states expanded Medicaid mental health parity requirements.',
