      letter: 'H',
      shortDef: 'Monthly oral or topical medication that kills heartworm larvae before they mature — essential in all 50 states, not just warm climates, for dogs and cats.',
      fullDef: 'Heartworm disease is caused by Dirofilaria immitis, a parasitic worm transmitted by mosquitoes. Adult worms live in the heart, lungs, and pulmonary vessels and can reach 12 inches in length. Dogs can harbor 25–100 worms; even a small number causes significant cardiopulmonary damage. Infection is irreversible — treatment exists for dogs but not cats.\n\nMonthly preventive medications (ivermectin-based products like Heartgard or milbemycin-based products like Interceptor) cost $6–$12/month for dogs. These drugs work by killing larvae deposited in the past 30 days — they don\'t kill adult worms or prevent infection, they kill the larval stage before it matures. Year-round prevention is recommended everywhere in the US; cases have been reported in all 50 states, and indoor pets are not immune since mosquitoes enter homes.\n\nHeartworm treatment, if infection occurs despite missed prevention, costs $900–$1,500 and requires 2–3 months of strict exercise restriction, multiple vet visits, and painful injections of melarsomine. Treatment is only available for dogs — cats with heartworm have no safe treatment option. Annual heartworm testing ($25–$45 antigen test) is required before prescribing preventives and catches any transmission failure.',
      example: 'A dog owner stopped giving heartworm prevention during winter, assuming the risk was seasonal; the dog tested positive the following spring. Treatment cost $1,200 plus 8 weeks of crate rest. Prevention would have cost $84 for the year.',
