      term: 'Hip Dysplasia',
      slug: 'hip-dysplasia',
      letter: 'H',
      shortDef: 'A developmental malformation of the hip joint where the ball and socket don\'t fit properly, causing pain, arthritis, and lameness — most common in large and giant breeds.',
      fullDef: 'Hip dysplasia occurs when the femoral head (ball) doesn\'t sit properly in the acetabulum (socket), causing abnormal wear, joint laxity, and eventually painful osteoarthritis. Large breeds most commonly affected include German Shepherds, Golden Retrievers, Labradors, Rottweilers, and Great Danes. The condition is polygenic and also influenced by growth rate, body weight, and nutrition — overfeeding large-breed puppies dramatically increases risk.\n\nDiagnosis is via radiographs. The OFA (Orthopedic Foundation for Animals) rates hips as Excellent, Good, Fair, Borderline, or Dysplastic on a scale based on x-rays taken at 24 months. The PennHIP method can screen puppies as young as 16 weeks using a distraction index. Reputable breeders of large breeds should have OFA or PennHIP certifications for both parents before breeding.\n\nTreatment ranges from medical management (joint supplements, NSAIDs, weight management, controlled exercise) for mild to moderate cases, to surgery for severe dysplasia. Total Hip Replacement (THR) — the gold standard — costs $3,500–$6,500 per hip and achieves excellent long-term outcomes. Triple Pelvic Osteotomy (TPO) in dogs under 10 months costs $2,800–$4,500. Daily joint supplements (glucosamine/chondroitin) cost $30–$60/month; fish oil at anti-inflammatory doses is supported by evidence.',
      example: 'A 2-year-old German Shepherd received a bilateral hip dysplasia diagnosis with severe OFA rating; one hip replacement cost $5,200 and restored near-normal function. The breeder had no OFA certifications on either parent.',
