      term: 'Brachycephalic Syndrome',
      slug: 'brachycephalic-syndrome',
      letter: 'B',
      shortDef: 'A collection of anatomical abnormalities in flat-faced (brachycephalic) breeds — including stenotic nares, elongated soft palate, and tracheal hypoplasia — that cause chronic breathing difficulty.',
      fullDef: 'Brachycephalic obstructive airway syndrome (BOAS) affects dogs and cats selectively bred for flattened facial features: French Bulldogs, English Bulldogs, Pugs, Boston Terriers, Shih Tzus, Boxers, and Persian cats, among others. The shortened skull compresses the same amount of soft tissue into a smaller space, resulting in stenotic nares (too-narrow nostrils), an elongated soft palate that obstructs the airway, a hypoplastic trachea (undersized windpipe), and everted laryngeal saccules.\n\nSymptoms include noisy breathing, exercise intolerance, overheating, snoring, gagging, and in severe cases, blue-tinged gums during exertion. Brachycephalic dogs are 20x more likely to develop heatstroke than non-brachycephalic breeds; airlines prohibit many brachycephalic breeds in cargo holds for this reason. The condition is progressive — soft palate abnormalities worsen with age as chronic negative pressure causes laryngeal changes.\n\nSurgical correction (soft palate resection, nare widening, laryngeal sacculectomy) costs $1,500–$4,000 and significantly improves quality of life if performed before secondary changes occur. French Bulldogs, the most popular dog breed in the US, have BOAS surgery rates of 25–35% by age 5. Prospective buyers should request BOAS grade assessments from breeders and budget for potential surgery.',
      example: 'A 3-year-old French Bulldog with grade 3 BOAS underwent soft palate and nare surgery costing $2,800; exercise tolerance improved dramatically and the dog no longer required air conditioning year-round to breathe comfortably.',
