      term: 'Flea and Tick Prevention',
      slug: 'flea-tick-prevention',
      letter: 'F',
      shortDef: 'Monthly or quarterly topical, oral, or collar-based products that kill or repel fleas, ticks, and sometimes mites — essential year-round in most US climates.',
      fullDef: 'Flea infestations are extremely difficult to eradicate once established: for every flea on the pet, an estimated 95% of the infestation (eggs, larvae, pupae) lives in the home environment. A single female flea lays 40–50 eggs per day. Full elimination typically requires treating the pet, all bedding, carpeting, and upholstered furniture simultaneously and may take 3–6 months.\n\nModern flea/tick preventives fall into three categories: oral isoxazolines (Bravecto, Nexgard, Simparica) which work systemically and are highly effective, lasting 30 days to 12 weeks depending on product; topical spot-ons (Frontline, Revolution, Advantage) applied to the skin; and imidacloprid-based collars (Seresto) lasting 8 months. Oral products cost $15–$30/month per dose. Seresto collars cost $50–$60 but amortize to under $10/month. OTC products (Hartz, Sentry) use older pesticide classes with lower efficacy and more adverse event reports.\n\nTick-borne diseases transmitted via ticks include Lyme disease (Borrelia, most common in Northeast and Midwest), Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever (Rickettsia, can be fatal), anaplasmosis, and ehrlichiosis. Lyme disease treatment in dogs costs $400–$600 for antibiotic courses; RMSF can require intensive hospitalization at $2,000–$5,000. Lyme vaccination ($30–$50/dose annually) is recommended for dogs in endemic areas in addition to tick prevention.',
