      shortDef: 'The FDA investigation (2018–2019) linking grain-free, legume-heavy diets to dilated cardiomyopathy (DCM) in dogs — a serious heart disease — which upended grain-free\'s "premium" marketing narrative.',
      fullDef: 'In 2018, the FDA began investigating a potential link between grain-free diets high in legumes (peas, lentils, chickpeas, potatoes) and dilated cardiomyopathy in dogs — including breeds not genetically predisposed to DCM like Golden Retrievers. Hundreds of cases were reported. The mechanism is not fully understood: the legume connection may be related to taurine bioavailability, total diet composition, or other factors.\n\nGrain-free diets became popular based on the marketing claim that grains are "fillers" harmful to dogs — a claim not supported by evidence. Dogs are omnivores with significantly longer digestive tracts than wolves and readily digest grains. Whole grains (brown rice, oatmeal, barley) provide digestible carbohydrates, fiber, and B vitamins. Food allergies in dogs are most commonly caused by animal proteins (beef, chicken, dairy), not grains.\n\nThe FDA investigation is ongoing and inconclusive; no definitive causal link has been established. However, the American College of Veterinary Internal Medicine recommends consulting a veterinarian before feeding grain-free diets, particularly for high-risk breeds (Golden Retrievers, Cocker Spaniels, Dobermans). Peer-reviewed evidence supports traditional grain-inclusive diets from established manufacturers with veterinary nutritionists on staff over boutique or grain-free alternatives.',
