      term: 'Socialization Window',
      slug: 'socialization-window',
      letter: 'S',
      shortDef: 'The critical developmental period (roughly 3–14 weeks for puppies, 3–7 weeks for kittens) when exposure to stimuli has lifelong effects on fearfulness and social behavior.',
      fullDef: 'The socialization window is a sensitive period in development when the brain actively forms positive associations with new experiences. During this window, exposure to a wide variety of people, animals, environments, sounds, handling, and surfaces with positive reinforcement builds resilience and reduces fear-based reactivity later in life. Conversely, negative or absent experiences during this window often produce persistent fear responses that are difficult or impossible to fully resolve in adulthood.\n\nFor dogs, the primary socialization window closes around 12–16 weeks, which creates a conflict with vaccine schedules — puppies are often kept isolated until "fully vaccinated" at 16 weeks, missing the most critical socialization period. The American Veterinary Society of Animal Behavior recommends that puppies attend properly run socialization classes starting at 7–8 weeks (after first set of vaccines), noting that the behavioral risk of inadequate socialization is greater than the infectious disease risk in a well-vaccinated class.\n\nUndersocialized dogs account for a disproportionate number of behavior problem cases seen by veterinary behaviorists. Fear-based behaviors (fear aggression, generalized anxiety, noise phobia) are the most common presenting complaint. Treatment with behavior modification, environmental management, and sometimes anxiolytic medications ($50–$150/month) helps but rarely achieves the outcomes of proper early socialization. Puppy classes ($100–$200 for 6 sessions) are among the highest-ROI investments in dog ownership.',
      example: 'Two Labrador puppies from the same litter: one attended puppy class at 9 weeks and was regularly exposed to children, strangers, umbrellas, and car rides; the other was kept isolated until 16 weeks. At age 2, the isolated dog required medication for severe noise phobia.',
