      slug: 'separation-anxiety',
      letter: 'S',
      shortDef: 'A panic disorder in dogs triggered by owner absence or departure cues — characterized by destructive behavior, vocalization, house soiling, and self-injury, not stubbornness or spite.',
      fullDef: 'True separation anxiety is a panic response, not a behavior problem. Affected dogs show physiological arousal (elevated cortisol, increased heart rate, panting) beginning at departure cue detection (picking up keys, putting on shoes). Behaviors — destructive chewing, barking, howling, inappropriate elimination, self-injury — occur only in the owner\'s absence and are not premeditated. Video monitoring is the gold standard for diagnosis since behaviors only occur when the owner is gone.\n\nSeverity ranges from mild distress (vocalization for 10–15 minutes then settling) to severe panic (non-stop distress, injury, destruction throughout absence). Mild cases respond well to behavioral protocols (systematic desensitization to departure cues, graduated absences). Severe cases typically require concurrent medication. Fluoxetine (the only FDA-approved drug for canine separation anxiety, sold as Reconcile) is effective and costs $40–$80/month; trazodone, clonidine, and alprazolam are also used situationally.\n\nA certified separation anxiety trainer (CSAT) specializes specifically in this condition. Remote session format (cameras + video calls) has made CSAT services more accessible at $500–$2,000 for a treatment package. Common mistakes that worsen anxiety include punishment (increases the association between owner absence and negative events), getting a second dog (doesn\'t address the underlying panic), and giving prolonged departing greetings.',
      example: 'A rescue Beagle destroyed a couch cushion and a door frame during a 4-hour absence. Video monitoring confirmed non-stop vocalization. A 16-week protocol combining fluoxetine and graduated desensitization with a CSAT resolved the behavior to less than 10 minutes of mild distress.',
