      fullDef: 'The OFA (Orthopedic Foundation for Animals) maintains a public database of health testing results for purebred dogs. Hip evaluations (most common) involve radiographs submitted to three OFA-certified radiologists who rate the hips as Excellent, Good, Fair (passing) or Borderline, Mild/Moderate/Severe Dysplasia (failing). Results are publicly searchable at ofa.org. Dogs receiving Excellent or Good ratings can receive an OFA number used in breeding programs.\n\nBeyond hips, OFA certifies elbow dysplasia, cardiac disease (congenital heart defects), thyroid, patellar luxation, autoimmune thyroiditis, congenital deafness (BAER testing), and breed-specific conditions. The CHIC (Canine Health Information Center) program sets breed-specific testing requirements — a Labrador achieving CHIC requires hip, elbow, EIC (exercise-induced collapse), and optometry clearances. Parents with CHIC numbers indicate a breeder investing in health screening.\n\nOFA screening costs breeders $35–$50 per evaluation. Buyers of large-breed puppies should require proof of OFA hip and elbow evaluations on both parents before purchasing. Buying a puppy without health testing from breeds predisposed to dysplasia is a gamble with significant financial and emotional consequences — hip replacement surgery costs $3,500–$6,500 per hip.',
      example: 'A buyer compared two Golden Retriever litters: one breeder had OFA Excellent hips and elbows on both parents with CHIC numbers; the other had no health testing documentation. The screened litter cost $400 more. The unscreened litter produced two puppies with dysplasia by age 2.',
