      fullDef: 'Emergency veterinary hospitals operate 24/7 and handle cases that cannot wait for regular office hours: toxin ingestion, trauma, GDV (bloat), urinary obstruction, respiratory distress, seizures, and severe wounds. These facilities have on-site diagnostics (digital radiograph, ultrasound, CT, bloodwork analyzers) and intensive care units.\n\nCosts are significantly higher than daytime practices. An emergency exam fee alone runs $100–$200. IV catheter placement and fluid therapy for a vomiting dog: $400–$700 overnight. GDV surgery (life-threatening stomach flip): $3,000–$8,000. Urinary obstruction in a male cat: $1,500–$3,500. Multi-day ICU hospitalization for pancreatitis: $2,500–$6,000. After-hours respiratory distress requiring oxygen therapy and diagnostics: $1,500–$3,000.\n\nThe reality is that most pet owners do not have $3,000–$5,000 in liquid savings for a pet emergency. Payment options include CareCredit and Scratchpay (veterinary-specific financing, 0% promotional periods), and the hospital\'s own payment plans. Pet insurance is the most effective financial mitigation — but must be purchased before any emergency occurs. An emergency fund specifically for pets of $2,000–$5,000 is the alternative if insurance premiums feel too high.',
      example: 'A 4-year-old Dachshund presented with sudden hind limb paralysis (IVDD disc extrusion); emergency MRI ($1,800), spinal surgery ($5,500), and 6 weeks of rehabilitation ($1,200) totaled $8,500. The owner had pet insurance; out-of-pocket after reimbursement was $1,100.',
