      letter: 'B',
      shortDef: 'Gastric Dilatation-Volvulus — a life-threatening emergency where the stomach fills with gas and twists on itself, cutting off blood supply; without surgery within hours, mortality approaches 100%.',
      fullDef: 'GDV is one of veterinary medicine\'s true emergencies. The stomach dilates with gas then rotates (volvulus), trapping gas inside and cutting off blood to the stomach wall and spleen. The trapped gas causes the dog to go into shock rapidly — within 4–6 hours of onset, cardiac arrhythmias, tissue necrosis, and systemic toxemia develop. Death occurs without surgical intervention.\n\nLarge, deep-chested breeds are disproportionately affected: Great Danes have a 37% lifetime risk, highest of any breed. Standard Poodles, Irish Setters, Gordon Setters, German Shepherds, and Dobermans are also high-risk. Suspected risk factors include eating a single large meal (vs. two smaller meals), rapid eating, elevated feeding bowls (paradoxically may increase risk), and genetic predisposition.\n\nEmergency stabilization (IV fluids, stomach decompression via trochar) followed by surgery costs $3,000–$8,000. Surgery involves deflating and untwisting the stomach and performing a gastropexy — suturing the stomach to the body wall to prevent recurrence. Prophylactic gastropexy (performed electively during spay/neuter) costs $300–$600 additional and is strongly recommended for high-risk breeds. Great Dane owners especially should know GDV signs: unproductive retching, distended abdomen, hypersalivation, restlessness.',
      example: 'A 7-year-old Great Dane owner recognized GDV signs at 11 PM and drove 40 minutes to an emergency hospital; surgery cost $6,200. The dog survived. A neighbor\'s Great Dane who hadn\'t received a prophylactic gastropexy died before reaching care.',
