      fullDef: 'The American Pet Products Association estimates that 70% of US households own pets, yet most underestimate lifetime costs at purchase. For a medium-to-large dog with a 12-year lifespan, annual costs average $1,500–$4,500, totaling $18,000–$54,000 over a lifetime. Cats are significantly cheaper: $500–$1,500/year, or $8,000–$20,000 over 15 years.\n\nMajor cost categories for dogs: food ($400–$1,200/year), veterinary care ($300–$800/year routine, much more if chronic conditions develop), flea/tick and heartworm prevention ($150–$400/year), boarding or pet sitting during vacations ($50–$85/night), grooming ($40–$100/session for long-coated breeds, 4–8 times/year), training ($200–$500 initial), and supplies. Large breeds cost more than small breeds; pure breeds from health-tested lines cost more upfront but may cost less in vet bills than poorly-bred dogs.\n\nBreed-specific health risks dramatically affect lifetime cost. A Frenchie with BOAS requiring surgery, a Golden Retriever with hip dysplasia, or a Dachshund with IVDD can add $5,000–$15,000+ in unplanned veterinary costs. Pet insurance budgeted annually ($480–$900/year) provides predictable cost in exchange for premium certainty. These numbers are why "the puppy is free" arrangements still result in thousands in lifetime expenditures.',
      example: 'A buyer paid $3,500 for a healthy, health-tested Golden Retriever puppy; over 11 years the total cost including food, routine vet care, one knee surgery, boarding, and supplies was $47,000. A "free" dog from an untested litter had $18,000 in vet costs in its first 5 years.',
