      fullDef: 'The American Veterinary Medical Association recognizes 22 specialty organizations covering disciplines including internal medicine, surgery, oncology, cardiology, dermatology, neurology, ophthalmology, and emergency/critical care. Board-certified specialists complete 3–5 years of residency after veterinary school and pass rigorous written and practical examinations. Not all vets who perform specialist services have this certification — verify DACVIM, DACVS, DACVO credentials.\n\nSpecialty consultation fees are significantly higher than general practice: initial exam $150–$350, procedures proportionally elevated. An oncology consult for a dog with lymphoma: $250–$400, plus CHOP chemotherapy protocol at $3,000–$5,000. Neurology MRI: $1,800–$2,500 for the scan plus interpretation. Dermatology allergy testing and immunotherapy: $400–$800 for testing, $100–$150/month for maintenance injections.\n\nGeneral practitioners handle 95%+ of pet health needs effectively. Referral to a specialist is warranted when: diagnosis is unclear after initial workup, a condition is not responding to standard treatment, surgery beyond the GP\'s skill level is needed, or a specialist-specific procedure (chemotherapy, radiation therapy, advanced imaging, specialized surgery) is required. Telemedicine specialist consultations ($40–$150) allow GP vets to get specialist input without the full referral cost.',
