      term: 'Meal Prep',
      slug: 'meal-prep',
      letter: 'M',
      shortDef: 'Batch cooking and portioning meals in advance — typically on weekends — to reduce daily cooking time, control macros and portions, reduce food costs, and improve dietary adherence.',
      fullDef: 'Meal prep involves preparing ingredients or complete meals ahead of time and storing them in portioned containers for use throughout the week. Approaches range from component prep (batch-cooking grains, proteins, and roasted vegetables stored separately for mix-and-match meals) to complete meal prep (fully assembled meals in individual containers, often identical across days) to hybrid approaches.\n\nFood safety guidelines govern meal prep storage: cooked proteins (chicken, beef, fish) last 3–4 days refrigerated; cooked grains and vegetables last 4–5 days; meals with eggs or dairy 3–4 days. Proper glass or BPA-free plastic containers with airtight lids prevent cross-contamination and maintain freshness. Freezing extends this substantially: cooked chicken lasts 3–4 months frozen, soups and stews 4–6 months.\n\nCost analysis: a meal-prepped lunch of chicken, rice, and broccoli costs approximately $2.50–$3.50 per serving in ingredients; the equivalent at a fast-casual restaurant costs $12–$16. A household that meal preps 5 lunches per week saves $40–$65 weekly — $2,000–$3,400 annually. Time investment is typically 2–3 hours per week vs. 30–45 minutes daily for meal decisions and preparation. Studies consistently link meal prepping to higher diet quality, greater fruit and vegetable intake, and better weight management outcomes.',
      example: 'A person starting a calorie-controlled diet batch-cooked 6 portions of salmon, 8 cups of brown rice, and 4 pounds of roasted vegetables on Sunday; each pre-portioned meal totaled 485 calories and $3.20 in ingredients, eliminating daily decision fatigue and fast food temptation.',
