      fullDef: 'Macronutrient tracking quantifies intake of the three primary macros: protein (4 cal/g), carbohydrates (4 cal/g), and fat (9 cal/g). Alcohol provides 7 cal/g with no macronutrient value. "Flexible dieting" or "If It Fits Your Macros" (IIFYM) uses macro targets rather than food rules, allowing any food as long as it fits within daily macro allocations — theoretically achieving body composition goals without rigid food restriction.\n\nMacro targets vary by goal. For muscle building: protein 0.7–1.0g per lb of bodyweight, slight caloric surplus (200–300 calories above TDEE). For fat loss: protein maintained at 0.7–1.0g/lb to preserve muscle, caloric deficit of 300–500 calories below TDEE. For performance: carbohydrate periodization around training. Protein is the most critical macro for body composition — high-protein diets preserve lean mass during caloric deficits and have the highest thermic effect (20–30% of protein calories burned during digestion vs. 5–10% for carbs, 0–3% for fat).\n\nApps: Cronometer is the most nutritionally comprehensive (tracks micronutrients, uses USDA database); MyFitnessPal has the largest food database including restaurant items; Lose It and Carbon Diet Coach use AI-based macro adjustments. Weighing food on a kitchen scale ($10–$20) rather than using measuring cups improves accuracy by 20–30% — volume measurements of foods like nuts, pasta, and meat can be significantly over or under actual weight.',
      example: 'A person tracking macros for fat loss set targets of 180g protein, 180g carbs, 60g fat (2,020 calories) with a 400-calorie deficit. Using Cronometer with a food scale, they hit targets within 5g/macro 5 days/week and lost 1.1 lbs/week on average over 12 weeks.',
