      shortDef: 'Dietary Approaches to Stop Hypertension — an evidence-based eating plan emphasizing fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and low-fat dairy while limiting sodium, red meat, and added sugars, shown to lower blood pressure by 8–14 mmHg.',
      fullDef: 'DASH was developed by NIH-funded researchers and tested in the DASH trial (New England Journal of Medicine, 1997) as a dietary intervention for hypertension. The eating plan provides 4–5 servings of fruits and vegetables per day, whole grains, low-fat dairy, lean proteins, nuts and legumes, and limits sodium to 1,500–2,300mg/day (standard American diet averages 3,400mg/day). The combination of high potassium, magnesium, calcium, and fiber while lowering sodium is the mechanism for blood pressure reduction.\n\nThe DASH-Sodium trial found that reducing sodium from 3,300mg to 1,500mg/day produced an additional 4–8 mmHg drop beyond the diet alone. Combined DASH + low sodium reduces systolic blood pressure by 8–14 mmHg in hypertensive individuals — comparable to first-line antihypertensive medications for stage 1 hypertension. US News & World Report has ranked DASH as the best overall diet for 13 consecutive years through 2024 for its nutritional completeness and evidence base.\n\nPractical implementation: increase fruits and vegetables to 8–10 servings daily (mostly non-starchy); choose low-sodium versions of canned goods; cook with herbs and spices instead of salt; choose whole grains (brown rice, oatmeal, whole wheat bread) over refined; limit alcohol to 1 drink/day or less. The diet requires no special foods or supplements — standard grocery shopping at $100–$150/week for a household of two covers all requirements.',
      example: 'A 52-year-old with blood pressure of 148/94 mmHg followed the DASH diet and reduced sodium intake for 3 months. Follow-up BP was 136/86 mmHg — an improvement sufficient to defer medication. The changes required no special foods, only different choices from the same grocery store.',
