      fullDef: 'FODMAPs (Fermentable Oligosaccharides, Disaccharides, Monosaccharides, and Polyols) are short-chain carbohydrates poorly absorbed in the small intestine that ferment in the colon, producing gas and drawing water — triggering bloating, cramping, diarrhea, and constipation in IBS sufferers. Developed by Monash University researchers, the low-FODMAP diet reduces these carbohydrates during phase 1, then systematically reintroduces each FODMAP subgroup in phase 2 to identify individual tolerance thresholds.\n\nHigh-FODMAP foods include: onions, garlic, wheat, milk, apples, honey, legumes, and cauliflower. Low-FODMAP alternatives: scallion greens, bell peppers, rice, oats, lactose-free dairy, strawberries, maple syrup, and green beans. The Monash University FODMAP app ($8, iOS/Android) is the gold-standard reference — it was developed by the diet\'s creators and is updated as new foods are tested. Phase 2 reintroduction takes 8–12 weeks to complete all subgroups.\n\n70–75% of IBS patients experience meaningful symptom reduction on low-FODMAP. The diet is nutritionally complete in the short term but challenging long-term due to restriction of beneficial prebiotic foods (onions, garlic, legumes feed gut microbiome). This is why phase 3 (personalization — returning tolerated FODMAPs to the diet) is critical and why the protocol should be done with a registered dietitian\'s guidance. Dietitian consult costs $100–$200/session; many insurance plans cover RD visits for IBS diagnosis.',
