      term: 'Maillard Reaction',
      slug: 'maillard-reaction',
      letter: 'M',
      shortDef: 'The chemical reaction between amino acids and reducing sugars that occurs above 280°F (138°C), producing the browning, crust, and complex flavors of seared meat, toasted bread, roasted coffee, and baked goods.',
      fullDef: 'The Maillard reaction (named for French chemist Louis-Camille Maillard, 1912) is the non-enzymatic browning reaction responsible for most of the flavor compounds in cooked food. It requires three conditions: amino acids (from proteins), reducing sugars, and sufficient heat — typically above 280°F (138°C), which is why boiling (212°F) produces pale, flavor-poor results while roasting and searing produce rich, browned flavors.\n\nFor the home cook, understanding Maillard reaction drives better technique: dry surface = more browning (pat proteins dry before searing — surface moisture steams food and lowers surface temperature below browning threshold); high heat = faster browning (cast iron or stainless steel at high heat sears faster than non-stick at medium); avoid crowding (too many items lower pan temperature, causing steaming instead of searing). The reaction also produces hundreds of flavor compounds including pyrazines (nutty/roasted), furanones (caramel-like), and thiophenes (meat-like).\n\nMaillard browning differs from caramelization (pure sugar thermal decomposition, requiring 320°F+) though both occur simultaneously in baked goods. Both create desirable flavors; both create acrylamide (a potential carcinogen formed in starchy foods at high heat) — which is why health guidelines suggest avoiding burnt or very dark browning of starchy foods (toast, fried potatoes). Moderate browning poses no meaningful health risk and greatly improves palatability.',
      example: 'A chicken breast seared in a dry cast iron pan at high heat (500°F surface) for 3 minutes per side developed a deeply browned crust with complex flavor. The same breast poached in water at 165°F was tender but pale and bland — the Maillard reaction never occurred.',
