      fullDef: 'Whole30 eliminates 9 food groups for 30 days: all added sugar (including honey, maple syrup, agave), all grains (wheat, oats, rice, corn, quinoa), all legumes (beans, lentils, peanuts, soy), all dairy, alcohol, carrageenan, sulfites, and MSG. Allowed foods: meat, seafood, eggs, vegetables, fruit, and most nuts and seeds. The rules are strict — a single non-compliant bite resets the 30-day clock.\n\nThe program was created by nutrition coaches Melissa and Dallas Hartwig in 2009. Proponents report improved energy, sleep, digestion, and skin as common outcomes. The 30-day format allows symptoms to resolve and provides enough data for meaningful reintroduction testing. Reintroduction protocol (days 31+) adds back each eliminated group separately over several weeks to identify which specific foods cause individual symptoms — similar in structure to the low-FODMAP protocol.\n\nCritical evaluation: Whole30 has no peer-reviewed clinical trials of its specific protocol. Eliminated food groups (legumes, grains, dairy) have substantial evidence for health benefits in other eating patterns (Mediterranean diet, DASH). The value of Whole30 appears to be in breaking habitual eating patterns and identifying genuine food sensitivities — not in the specific foods eliminated. Cost increases because processed foods (with non-compliant additives) are eliminated, requiring whole-food cooking; budget for $100–$200 more per month in groceries.',
