      shortDef: 'Interpreting nutrition facts panels and ingredient lists to understand actual nutritional content — including serving size manipulation, hidden sugars, and marketing claims that obscure product quality.',
      fullDef: 'The Nutrition Facts label (mandatory on packaged US foods since 1994, updated format since 2020) lists serving size, calories, macronutrients, selected micronutrients, and % Daily Values based on a 2,000-calorie diet. Serving sizes were updated in 2020 to reflect realistic portions (a cookie that was listed as "2 cookies per serving" when most people eat 5 is now listed at realistic amounts). Always multiply nutrition values by the number of servings you actually consume.\n\nIngredient lists are ordered by weight (descending). The first 3 ingredients make up the majority of the product. "Sugar" appears under 50+ names: cane juice, maltodextrin, dextrose, fructose, barley malt, fruit juice concentrate, sorbitol — checking for multiple sugar synonyms in the first 5 ingredients identifies high-sugar products disguised by sugar name diversification. "Natural flavor" is a legally defined term covering thousands of substances; it guarantees natural origin but not specific content or safety for all sensitivities.\n\nMarketing claims on the front are largely unregulated: "made with whole grains" (may contain 5% whole grain), "multigrain" (multiple refined grains), "reduced fat" (fat reduced 25% vs. regular, but may have added sugar). The actual nutrition panel and ingredient list are the reliable information sources. USDA organic certification means 95%+ organic ingredients, no synthetic pesticides, and no GMOs — it\'s a verified claim with third-party auditing, unlike "natural" which has no regulatory definition.',
