      term: 'Shoulder Season',
      slug: 'shoulder-season',
      letter: 'S',
      shortDef: 'The travel period immediately before or after peak season — offering lower prices, smaller crowds, and often the best combination of weather and value for budget-conscious travelers.',
      fullDef: 'Shoulder season falls between peak season (highest prices, most visitors) and off-season (lowest prices, potential closures). For most small-town destinations: spring (April–May) and fall (September–October) represent shoulder season, with summer and holiday weekends as peak. Beach towns are opposite in some regions — spring and fall see strong demand, winter is quiet.\n\nPricing differences are substantial. A mountain-town B&B that charges $250/night in peak foliage season may cost $110–$130 in shoulder season. Restaurant wait times drop from 90 minutes to walk-in availability. Shoulder season travel 2–4 weeks before peak often captures 80% of the scenery or experience at 50–60% of the cost. In New England, early October leaf season commands premium pricing identical to peak summer; late October drops 30–40% with comparable foliage.\n\nFor small-town destinations specifically, shoulder season has an additional advantage: locally owned businesses are less overwhelmed and provide more personal service. Artisan shops, local guides, and historic sites have more availability. Research whether key attractions have consistent hours in shoulder season — some seasonal businesses (farm stands, outdoor outfitters) operate reduced hours or close mid-week. Call ahead for independently owned lodging and restaurants.',
      example: 'A couple planning a wine country weekend in Sonoma compared rates: Saturday night peak-summer lodging at a boutique inn cost $425; the same room the first weekend of November (shoulder season) was $195, restaurants had no wait, and tasting rooms encouraged lingering conversation rather than rushing tables.',
