      fullDef: 'Bed and breakfasts are small lodging establishments (typically under 12 rooms) operated by on-site owners, distinguishing them from boutique hotels and inns. The morning meal — ranging from continental to elaborate multi-course affairs — is included in the room rate and often features local ingredients, house-made items, and communal dining that encourages guest interaction. Rates typically run $100–$300/night depending on location, season, and amenities.\n\nThe PAII (Professional Association of Innkeepers International) estimates 10,000–17,000 B&Bs operate in the US. Quality varies enormously — ratings on TripAdvisor, Yelp, and Google reflect the specific property rather than a brand standard. Booking directly through the property often saves 10–15% versus OTA (Online Travel Agency) platforms like Booking.com or Expedia, and supports the owner more fully.\n\nB&Bs offer genuine differentiation from chain hotels: hosts with local knowledge provide restaurant recommendations, insider walking tour suggestions, and can arrange experiences unavailable to standard visitors. Bathrooms may be private or shared (always confirmed at booking). Policies on children, pets, and minimum-night stays vary by property and should be reviewed before booking. Cancellation policies are often stricter than hotel chains — travel insurance ($50–$100/trip) protects non-refundable deposits.',
