      shortDef: 'Travel motivated by experiencing the authentic history, architecture, culture, and stories of a place — one of the fastest-growing travel segments, generating $192 billion annually in the US.',
      fullDef: 'Heritage tourism encompasses visits to historic sites, historic districts, museums, cultural events, and places associated with distinctive historical narratives. The National Trust for Historic Preservation defines heritage travelers as those who "visit historic sites, museums, and cultural events" — surveys find they spend 36% more per trip and stay longer than non-heritage travelers. Small towns with preserved Main Streets, Civil War sites, industrial history, or ethnic heritage are natural beneficiaries.\n\nNational Register of Historic Places designation (administered by the National Park Service) is the federal benchmark for historic significance. Over 95,000 properties are listed. Listing doesn\'t restrict private use but signals authentic historic character and sometimes provides access to state historic tax credits for restoration. State heritage tourism programs (Virginia Tourism, Pennsylvania Heritage, etc.) produce maps, driving tours, and promotional materials for heritage travelers.\n\nHeritage tourism spending is dominated by older, higher-income travelers: the average heritage tourist is 47, holds a college degree, and earns above $50,000. This demographic drives demand for quality lodging, dining at locally owned restaurants, and artisan shopping — precisely what small-town economies offer at their best. Local heritage tourism offices can connect travelers with walking tour apps, historic home tours, guided experiences, and living history events.',
      example: 'A couple visiting Galena, Illinois, a Civil War-era mining town, spent 3 nights in a restored 1855 inn, took a guided walking tour ($18/person), dined at restaurants in 19th-century storefronts, and purchased locally made pottery — spending $890 that stayed almost entirely in the local economy.',
