      fullDef: 'Agritourism bridges agriculture and tourism, allowing visitors to engage with working farms, ranches, and agricultural operations. The USDA Census of Agriculture reports that 28,000+ US farms earn income from agritourism, with farm-related attractions generating $1.05 billion annually (2017 census). Popular activities include: u-pick orchards and berry farms ($15–$30 per person entry/produce credit), pumpkin patches, corn mazes, farm-to-table dinners, farm stays (sleep in a renovated farmhouse or glamping tent on working farmland, $150–$350/night), winery/vineyard tours, and seasonal harvest festivals.\n\nU-pick operations offer both an experience and price-competitiveness with retail — strawberries at a u-pick farm run $1.50–$2.50/lb versus $3–$5/lb at grocery stores, with the experience included. Farm-to-table dinners hosted on the farm property combine cuisine with setting at $75–$175 per person. Glamping on farm properties grew 25% annually between 2015–2023, driven by travelers seeking rural authenticity without camping discomfort.\n\nFor small-town visitors, agritourism provides structured access to rural experiences that would otherwise be inaccessible. Check PickYourOwn.org for u-pick locations by state/crop and Harvest Hosts (membership platform, $99/year) for overnight stays at wineries, farms, and breweries. Agritourism seasons are highly specific — call ahead to confirm harvest timing, which varies by 2–4 weeks based on weather.',
