      shortDef: 'The US federal list of districts, sites, buildings, and structures deemed worthy of preservation — maintained by the National Park Service — serving as a heritage tourism signal and enabling state tax credit access.',
      fullDef: 'The National Register of Historic Places is the official federal list recognizing places of historic, architectural, archaeological, or cultural significance. Administered by the NPS under the National Historic Preservation Act (1966), it includes 95,000+ properties nationwide ranging from individual buildings to entire historic districts. Listing on the National Register does not restrict owner use or require public access — it primarily confers honor, visibility, and eligibility for federal and state preservation programs.\n\nFor travelers, National Register designation provides reliable authentication of historic character. The NPS maintains a searchable database (nps.gov/nr) where travelers can find listed properties by state and county. Many small towns have Historic Districts listed on the National Register — these typically encompass the Main Street commercial corridor and surrounding residential neighborhoods with preserved 19th-century architecture.\n\nFor property owners and local developers, National Register listing enables access to the Federal Historic Tax Credit — a 20% income tax credit for qualified rehabilitation of income-producing historic properties. Many states add 10–25% additional credits, making total incentives of 30–45% of rehabilitation costs possible. This financing mechanism has driven $100+ billion in historic preservation investment since 1976 and explains why many small-town Main Streets have been restored to economic vitality.',
