      slug: 'state-scenic-byway',
      letter: 'S',
      shortDef: 'A state-designated road recognized for exceptional scenic, historic, natural, or recreational qualities — often connecting small towns along a themed corridor with interpretive signage and traveler services.',
      fullDef: 'State scenic byway programs (all 50 states have programs) designate roads with outstanding intrinsic qualities across six categories: scenic, natural, historic, cultural, archaeological, and recreational. The Federal Highway Administration\'s America\'s Byways program recognizes exceptional byways at the national level — 184 routes as of 2024 covering 31,000 miles. Byway designation typically comes with improved signage, interpretive pull-offs, associated visitor guides, and smartphone apps with audio tours.\n\nByways provide ready-made road trip frameworks for small-town exploration. Virginia has 24 scenic byways; Pennsylvania\'s Scenic Byways program covers 25 routes; Georgia\'s Tourism Scenic Byways connect 53 designated routes. The Natchez Trace Parkway (444 miles, Tennessee to Mississippi), Blue Ridge Parkway (469 miles, Virginia to North Carolina), and Great River Road (3,000 miles along the Mississippi) are among the most visited. Byway routing intentionally avoids interstates — the drive itself is part of the experience.\n\nFor trip planning, the National Scenic Byways Program website (byways.org) and America\'s Byways app provide routing, points of interest, and lodging along each route. State tourism offices publish physical maps and guides. Driving a byway versus an interstate typically adds 30–60 minutes per 100 miles but delivers fundamentally different scenic and cultural exposure at no additional cost.',
      example: 'A road tripper drove Ohio\'s Amish Country Byway (50 miles) instead of US-30, passing through Berlin, Walnut Creek, and Kidron. Travel time added 25 minutes but included stops at 3 Amish-owned businesses, a historic covered bridge, and a farm stand selling fresh-made cheese — experiences unavailable on the highway.',
