      shortDef: 'A recurring marketplace where local producers sell directly to consumers — providing fresh, seasonal, often local and organic products while offering travelers authentic connection to regional food culture.',
      fullDef: 'US farmers markets numbered 8,600+ in USDA\'s 2019 count, operating in every state and most counties. For travelers, farmers markets offer both practical (fresh food for road trip provisions) and experiential value — they concentrate local producers, artisans, prepared food vendors, and community character in a single accessible location. Markets typically operate Saturday mornings year-round in warmer climates and seasonally in cold-weather states.\n\nQuality varies considerably. True farmers markets (USDA designation requires "producer-only" rules) sell only what vendors grow, raise, or produce. Some markets allow resellers — vendors who buy wholesale and sell as if local. The "Certified Farmers Market" designation in California and similar state programs enforce producer-only rules. Ask vendors directly what they grow/raise and where — authentic producers have specific, knowledgeable answers; resellers often deflect.\n\nFarmers markets typically price fresh produce 20–40% above supermarket prices for common items, but often below for specialty, heirloom, or certified organic products. The premium buys freshness (often harvested within 48 hours), variety (50+ apple cultivars vs. 4 at a grocery store), and direct producer relationship. For travelers, a Saturday morning farmers market visit often provides the most concentrated exposure to local food culture of any single activity.',
