      fullDef: 'The Leave No Trace (LNT) framework provides seven principles for outdoor visitors: 1) Plan ahead and prepare (know regulations, weather, terrain); 2) Travel and camp on durable surfaces (stay on trails, use established campsites); 3) Dispose of waste properly (pack it in, pack it out; human waste 200 feet from water in a cathole 6–8 inches deep); 4) Leave what you find (no picking flowers, removing rocks, disturbing artifacts); 5) Minimize campfire impact (use fire rings, only in permitted areas, small fires, use dead and downed wood, fully extinguish); 6) Respect wildlife (observe from distance, no feeding, store food properly); 7) Be considerate of other visitors (yield to uphill hikers, dogs on leash where required, manage noise).\n\nLNT principles are not laws but ethics — visitor behavior gaps cause 80%+ of human-caused trail and campsite degradation. Popular small-town outdoor recreation areas increasingly post LNT reminders at trailheads due to "Instagram tourism" effects: visitors following geotagged social media posts to fragile locations without context. Yelp and AllTrails show crowds, not conditions.\n\nFor travelers to small towns with outdoor recreation access: check land management agency websites (NPS, USFS, BLM, state parks) for current regulations, fire restrictions, and camping rules — these change seasonally and after weather events. State park day-use fees range from $5–$15/vehicle; overnight camping $20–$45/site. Reservations are essential for popular sites: recreation.gov (federal), reserve.america.com (state parks).',
