      fullDef: 'Effective road trip routing involves identifying a "spine" (main directional route), clustering stops geographically to minimize driving, and building loops or point-to-point paths based on transportation logistics. For small-town tourism, clustering 3–4 towns within a 50-mile radius per day creates depth without excessive driving — each stop becomes more meaningful when time pressure is lower.\n\nDigital tools have transformed road trip planning: Google Maps and Apple Maps support multi-stop routing (up to 9 waypoints on Google), but Roadtrippers ($35/year), Furkot (free), and Wanderlog (free) are specifically designed for trip planning with points of interest integration. Furkot is particularly useful for optimizing stop sequence. Gas cost calculators (GasBuddy, AAA TripTik) project fuel costs accurately with real-time prices and vehicle MPG input.\n\nPractical timing: budget 30–40 minutes of driving time per 25 miles on rural two-lane roads (slower than highway pace plus turns), 15–20 minutes per highway mile. Add 50% buffer for rural driving over digital map estimates. Restaurant lunch hours in small towns are strict (11:30am–1:30pm); arriving outside that window means limited options. Arrive before 5pm for boutique lodging check-in flexibility. Download offline maps (Google Maps or maps.me) for cell coverage gaps common in rural small-town corridors.',
