      fullDef: 'The National Main Street Center (a program of the National Trust for Historic Preservation) operates the Main Street America network — over 1,200 designated communities committed to downtown revitalization using historic preservation as the foundation. The "Four Points" framework guides participating communities: Design (historic rehabilitation), Economic Vitality (business retention and recruitment), Promotion (events and marketing), and Organization (management and funding).\n\nMain Street communities have collectively generated $92 billion in investment and 160,000 net new businesses since 1980 per program data. For travelers, the Main Street America program website (mainstreet.org) provides a searchable directory of all designated communities — each represents a town with organizational commitment to authentic character, locally owned businesses, and historic preservation.\n\nLocally owned businesses are the economic signal: chain businesses pay their profits to distant corporate headquarters; locally owned businesses recirculate 3x more spending locally per dollar spent. A $50 dinner at a locally owned restaurant generates approximately $43 of local economic impact vs. $14 at a chain. Independent retail, local restaurants, and craft producers are concentrated in successful Main Street communities. Travelers who prioritize locally owned spending have disproportionate economic impact relative to spend.',
