      fullDef: 'Ghost towns result from the exhaustion of the economic driver that founded them: mining played out, railroad routes shifted, agricultural conditions failed, or industry relocated. The American West contains the highest concentration — California alone has 200+ documented ghost towns from the Gold Rush era (1849–1860s). Bodie State Historic Park (California), Calico Ghost Town (California), Jerome (Arizona, partially inhabited), and Bannack State Park (Montana) are among the most visited.\n\nGhost town accessibility ranges from drive-in paved roads to backcountry 4WD trails requiring high-clearance vehicles. Research thoroughly before visiting remote sites — many historical maps show ghost towns that exist today only as foundations or are on private mining claims. BLM (Bureau of Land Management) manages most Western ghost towns on public land; state parks preserve the most significant sites with interpretive infrastructure. Collecting artifacts from ghost towns on public land violates the Archaeological Resources Protection Act (ARPA) — fines up to $20,000, imprisonment up to 2 years.\n\nGhost towns near small active towns create tourism ecosystems: visitors to Bodie (20 miles from Bridgeport, CA) stay in Bridgeport, eat at local restaurants, and buy supplies there. "Gateway towns" to ghost town clusters benefit economically from heritage tourists. Photography is the most common ghost town activity — golden hour light on weathered wood produces exceptional images, driving significant Instagram-era visitation to previously unknown sites.',
